<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Seeking to Improve Energy Efficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Singapore has mounted efforts to
improve its energy efficiency in a bid to achieve its development
and environmental objectives, a senior Singapore official said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Over the years, we have developed policies and implemented
many measures to improve the energy efficiency in the different
sectors," Koo Tsai Kee, senior parliamentary secretary of the
Ministry of National Development, said at the opening of the "
Germany-Singapore Environmental Technology Agency: Asia-Pacific
Regional Workshop on Energy Efficiency."
</P>
<P>
He said that in the industrial and transport sectors as well
as residential and commercial buildings, the three main sectors
for energy consumption in Singapore, energy-saving programs have
been undertaken in each sector. They include setting up the Public
Utility Board to provide services and advice on energy
conservation, adopting an energy auditing system, offering tax
incentives, replacing older energy inefficient equipment,
improving public housing designs and managing the growth and usage
of private vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's current efforts are not enough, he said, noting
that Singapore's average GDP growth was about 7.6 percent per
annum during the 1980 to 1995 period while energy demand over the
same period grew at an average 11.9 percent and Singapore ranked
the 25th out of 45 countries in energy intensity or the amount of
commercial energy consumed per dollar GDP.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless, there is ample room for Singapore to improve on
its energy efficiency performance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Figures from a study by the ministry show that by installing
energy efficient refrigerators and air conditioning units,
respective 26 percent and 8 percent energy savings can be achieved,
he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said energy savings of similar magnitudes can also be
achieved in commercial, institutional and industrial buildings.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the manufacturing sector where motors are
estimated to use three-quarters of the industry's electricity, he
said a 12-fold energy saving could be achieved after some of its
processes are re-engineered.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's overall electricity consumption is projected to
increase at an average of 5.3 percent per annum and the country
needs to boost its generating capacity by 60 percent before 2007,
Koo said.
</P>
<P>
Over the next 40 years, he added, an estimated 570 to 720
hectares of land will have to be set aside for power plants and
transmission stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
