<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls for Israeli Troop Withdrawal from All Arab Lands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
said on Wednesday that he hopes the Israeli troop withdrawal from
Lebanon will pave the way for an overall Israeli pullout from all
occupied Arab lands and for a comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in a meeting with Israeli Minister of Public
Security Shlom Ben-Ami, who arrived here earlier in the day to
brief the monarch on the situation on the Israeli-Lebanese border
after the pullout as well as developments of Israel's peace talks
with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli minister said his country will adhere to its
commitments to the peace process and will strive to strike a
framework agreement of final peace with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah stressed the need for a just, durable and comprehensive
peace in the region and called on the parties concerned to overcome
all obstacles standing in the peace talks and to work on peace,
stability and prosperity of the region.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the Jordanian house of deputies (lower house
of parliament) hailed the Israeli troop withdrawal from south
Lebanon as a liberation of Lebanese territories and a logical
result of 22 years of anti-aggression efforts by the Lebanese
people.
</P>
<P>
In a brief statement, the Jordanian house also called on the
world community to pressure Israel to withdraw its troops from all
occupied Arab territories, including Palestinian lands and the
Golan Heights it captured from Syria during the 1967 Middle East
war, and to recognize an independent Palestinian state with
Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
For years, Jordan has been a major peace broker between Israel
and its Arab neighbors since it signed a peace treaty with Israel
in 1994, the second Arab country after Egypt to reach a peace deal
with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Israeli forces invaded and occupied southern Lebanon in 1978 to
prevent cross-border attacks and installed a 850-square-kilometer
security zone in south Lebanon for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
Upon an order from Prime Minister Ehud Barak, the Jewish state
pulled out all its soldiers peacefully from south Lebanon by
Wednesday morning ahead of its self-imposed deadline in July.
</P>
<P>
Most analysts believe that dramatic Israeli troop withdrawal is
partly due to mounting casualties under guerrilla attacks. Seven
Israeli soldiers died in the security zone this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
