<HEADLINE> Egypt, Morocco Reiterate Support for Palestinians, Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Morocco underlined their
full support on Wednesday to the Palestinian people's rights,
including their right to establish an independent state with
Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement issued after a meeting of the Egyptian-
Moroccan Joint Higher Committee said the two countries oppose and
reject Israel's settlement policies in the occupied Palestinian
territories and its attempts to judaize Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The statement stressed that Israel's policies hinder the way to
the realization of a just and comprehensive peace in the Middle
East, which the peoples in the region aspire for.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Moroccan King Mohammad VI
co-chaired the fourth session of the two countries' joint committee
on regional issues and ways of further promoting political and
economic cooperation. The Moroccan monarch wrapped up a three-day
official visit earlier Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want Arab East Jerusalem as the capital of
their future independent state. But Israel, which occupied that
part of the holy city in the 1967 Mideast War, has claimed
Jerusalem as its "undivided and eternal capital." The two sides are
working to solve the dispute, among other thorny issues, in the
final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
In their joint statement, Egypt and Morocco also voiced support
for Syria's legitimate right to recover the Golan Heights that
Israel occupied from Syria in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Israel broke off their peace talks in January due to
disputes over Israeli withdrawal from the strategic plateau and
control of water resource.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Morocco called for adherence to the relevant United
Nations Security Council resolutions and the land-for-peace
principle by concerned parties in seeking peaceful settlement of
the decades-old Arab-Israeli conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
