<HEADLINE> Upgrading of Proximity Talks on Cyprus Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Greek Cypriot AKEL party and Turkish
Cypriot Republic Party (TRP) Wednesday noted the need to upgrade
the U.N.-sponsored proximity talks on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus News Agency, AKEL leader Demetris
Christofias and TRP leader Ali Talat Wednesday held a three-hour
meeting at the AKEL headquarters in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
A joint communique issued after the meeting warned that the loss
of time for a solution in Cyprus might pose serious dangers for
both communities.
</P>
<P>
It urged the present procedure of proximity talks to be upgraded
so that the talks become a substantive direct dialogue between the
leaders of the two communities.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern island after a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of U.N.-sponsored proximity talks between the two
communities have been held, with an aim to prepare the ground for
substantive talks which may lead to a comprehensive solution of the
Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two sides put forward their positions and
gave clarifications, but there has been no negotiation as such.
</P>
<P>
A third round of talks is scheduled to begin in Geneva on July
5.
</P>
<P>
The joint communique of AKEL and TRP called on the leaders of
the two communities to come to the negotiating table without any
conditions and to work decisively for a solution.
</P>
<P>
The two parties expressed their support to a peaceful solution
that will safeguard the independence, territorial integrity and
sovereignty of the bizonal, bicommunal federal Republic of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
They also pledged to continue working toward promoting contact
and restoration of trust between the two communities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
