<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Says Priority Remains Unchanged on Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Wednesday said that the priority remained unchanged to secure the
release of remaining U.N. peacekeepers, held by rebels in Sierra
Leone, and called on the rebels "immediately and unconditionally"
release all the remaining hostages.
</P>
<P>
This was contained in a statement prepared for the press by
the president of the Security Council, Wang Yingfan of China,
after the 15-nation Council met in a closed-door session to
discuss the latest developments in Sierra Leone, where hundreds of
U.N. soldiers are still being held by the rebel Revolutionary
United Front (RUF).
</P>
<P>
"Council members stressed that the clear priority continues to
be the release of the U.N. peacekeepers detained by the RUF," the
statement said. "Council members demand that the RUF release,
immediately and unconditionally, all remaining detainees."
</P>
<P>
"Council members expressed their grave concern at the reports
of the discovery of the bodies, possibly of U.N. peacekeepers, at
Rogberi junction, emphasized that the RUF is responsible for the
fate of these U.N. personnel," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Council members call on all those with influence with the RUF
including (Liberian) President (Charles) Taylor to insist that
this take place forthwith," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Council members expressed their deep concern over the
humanitarian situation in Sierra Leone," the statement said. "
Council members reminded all States their obligations to implement
the arms embargo against the RUF and expressed their willingness
to consider further measures to strengthen the sanctions regime."
</P>
<P>
Council members were briefed on the latest developments in the
West African country by U.N. Assistant Secretary-General Hedi
Annabi, and the meeting was held shortly after U.N. Secretary-
General Kofi Annan promised efforts to get the rest of the
detainees into freedom.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the U.N. Headquarters in New York
Wednesday, Annan told reporters, "We are all working hard."
</P>
<P>
Liberian President Charles Taylor, who mediated the release of
the detainees, said Wednesday that RUF leader Foday Sankoh, who
currently remains in the custody, needs to be involved in any
negotiation for the release of the detainees.
</P>
<P>
"Let me say that I did speak to President Taylor myself on the
release of the remaining detainees, and we are all working hard,
and, of course, he expects to be able to see some more of the
detainees released before the end of the week," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"There's going to be a meeting in Abuja -- West African heads
of state -- on Saturday," he said. "And of course, I would hope
that, by the time they meet, most of the peacekeepers will be in
freedom."
</P>
<P>
On the bodies that were found in U.N. uniform in bushes in
Sierra Leone, Annan said, "I have not gotten a detailed analysis
as to whether they are really some of our peacekeepers and what
they are, so I would prefer not to comment on that at this stage."
</P>
<P>
Annan, in his written report to the Security Council Monday,
called on the U.N. Mission in Sierra Leone (UNAMSIL) to be
increased by 3,500 to 16,500 military personnel. This is the first
report by Annan on the situation in Sierra Leone since rebels took
U.N. peacekeepers hostage in early May.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council Friday unanimously adopted a resolution to
increase personnel to 13,000.
</P>
<P>
The RUF abducted more than 500 U.N. peacekeepers and civilians
in early May. About 250 U.N. personnel are still being held
hostage in the West African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
