<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Major U.S. Airlines to Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Washington, May 24 (Xinhua) -- UAL Corp., the largest airline
in the United States, has agreed to buy US Airways, the nation's
sixth-largest airline, for 4.3 billion U.S. dollars in cash, the
companies said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The deal would give the UAL Corp., parent company of the United
Airlines, vastly larger operations along the East Coast and nearly
triple its daily flights to more than 6,400 a day.
</P>
<P>
UAL will pay 60 dollars in cash for each US Airways share, a
131 percent premium over US Airways' closing price in trading
Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the cash, UAL Corp. will assume 7.3 billion
dollars in debt and aircraft operating leases as part of the deal.
A combined company would have more than 25 billion dollars in
annual revenue and more than 145,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
The companies said their frequent-flier programs will be
consolidated, and will offer more destinations than any other
airline. United is part of the international Star Alliance, which
includes Air Canada and Lufthansa among others, and has a separate
mileage-sharing deal with Delta Airlines. US Airways and American
Airlines, the world's second-largest airline, have their own
mileage partnership.
</P>
<P>
With about 2,300 flights a day, United flies more than 570 jets
to more than 130 destinations in the United States and 25 other
countries. US Airways and the regional carrier US Airways Express
offer about 4,100 flights daily in 38 states and 12 countries.
</P>
<P>
In announcing the deal, United said it would offer 64 new daily
nonstop domestic flights and 29 overseas flights.
</P>
<P>
The two airlines tried to merge in 1995, but failed after
United's powerful pilots' lobby exerted pressure. United is 55
percent owned by its employees; their approval will be necessary
for any deal to succeed.
</P>
<P>
Antitrust regulators may not let the acquisition go through
unscathed. The Justice Department has sued to challenge Northwest
Airlines' acquisition of a controlling stake in Continental
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
As part of the deal, UAL will sell some operations in
Washington, D.C., to entrepreneur Robert L. Johnson, who will form
DC Air, the nation's first black-owned airline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Equity Prices Down Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The equity prices in Greece
Wednesday dropped sharply with the general index on the Athens
Stock Exchange (ASE) falling 2.59 percent to 4,551.12 points.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE/ASE 20 index ended 1.79 percent lower at 2,527.29
points while the FTSE/ASE 40 index dropped 3.81 percent to 659.11
points.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 197 billion drachmas (about 532 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Decliners led advancers by 317 to 22 with another three issues
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The investment and construction sectors led the dropping stock
market by plunging 7.47 percent and 5.70 percent respectively.
</P>
