<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nurses Stage Biggest Strike in Alberta, Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of nurses Wednesday staged
the biggest strike across Canada's western province of Alberta to
press for a wage increase of at least 15 percent over two years.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 10,000 licensed practical nurses, nursing attendants and
other support staff went off work at 159 hospitals and long-term
care facilities in the province following overnight negotiations
without results.
</P>
<P>
The local court termed the strike as illegal, saying the
Alberta Labor Relations Board filed a ruling Tuesday in the Court
of Queen's Bench ordering the union to stop planning or
threatening a strike.
</P>
<P>
A union leader was served a summons Wednesday morning for
disobeying the court order.
</P>
<P>
One of the parties involved in the negotiations, the Alberta
Union of Provincial Employees, vowed to go on striking for both
wages and job security.
</P>
<P>
The union asked for a wage increase of between 15 percent and
23 percent over two years, while management offered 12.2 percent
over three years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, contingency is being managed for urgent surgeries
including cancer and cardiac operations, local health officials
say.
</P>
<P>
The union has also promised to continue providing some
essential services to minimize the danger to patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
