<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Winter Wave in Colombia Causes 32 Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- A winter wave affecting Colombia,
mainly in its southern part, has caused 32 dead, according to a
report from rescue organizations released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Institute of Hydrology, Meteorology and
Environmental Studies (IHMES) forecasted the reactivation of rains
all over the national territory.
</P>
<P>
Intense raining since last weekend affected the provinces of
Narino, Putumayo and Santander, and in the last hours Tolima and
other regions in the country as well, causing many casualties,
with 49 disappearing and 17,000 victims.
</P>
<P>
In Putumayo ,in the border with Peru and Ecuador, authorities
confirmed 14 people died and 18 disappeared. An initial balance
shows there are 2,4000 families affected and a surface of 1,900
hectares of cropland lost.
</P>
<P>
At Pasto, capital of Narino, other seven people lost their
lives because of the rain in the last hours. Last Sunday there
were 11 casualties.
</P>
<P>
The IHMES warned that the mathematical simulation models allow
to establish the increase in downpour in the departments of Nario,
Caldas, Quindio, Risaralda, Tolima, Antioquia, Choco, Santander,
North Santander, North Cundinamarca, West Boyaco and in the Valley
of Cauca.
</P>
<P>
The climate variations will bring with them the increase in
river flows of high slope, landslides, and debris accumulation in
some river basins.
</P>
<P>
Also, there are reports of high increases in the rivers Coello,
Luisa, Medina and Combeima (Tolima), in which there could be,
according to forecasts, floodings.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the level of the rivers Pasto, Narino,
Putumayo, Caqueta (south) and Catatumbo in North Santander
continues to rise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
