<HEADLINE> Expansion of Trade Relations With Iran Proper: Turkish Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Despite the tension in political
relations with Iran, Sermet Atacanli, deputy spokesman of the
Turkish Foreign Ministry, said on Wednesday that the forthcoming
visit of a Turkish trade delegation to Iran would be "appropriate".
</P>
<P>
A delegation of 100 businessmen headed by Undersecretary of
Foreign Trade Office Kursad Tuzmen will go to Iran on Saturday to
explore bilateral economic cooperation and attend a meeting of the
Border Trade Joint Committee which held a meeting in Turkey in last
May.
</P>
<P>
Due to the allegations about Iranian involvement in murders of
Turkish journalists and intellectuals, the Turkey Foreign Ministry
had earlier asked Tuzmen to review the decision to visit Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry made the statement on the visit following
the Foreign Trade Office asked it to assess the political and trade
ties with Iran separately.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey should develop trade relations with its neighbors
independent from its political relations," the Foreign Ministry
announced.
</P>
<P>
Atacanli said, however, that they have not issued an official
statement over whether President Ahmet Sezer will attend the
Economic Cooperation Organization (ECO) meeting to be held in
Tehran on June 5.
</P>
<P>
Both countries will benefit from good bilateral relations, the
spokesman said, adding that "certainly there are some issues which
are sensitive for Turkey. We expect the Iranian side to show the
same sensitivity towards them."
</P>
<P>
Reports said the Turkish police had arrested nine Islamic
activists recently, and some Turkish press accused Iran of being
involved in the killing of two Turkish journalists in 1993 and
1999.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman said that detained Iranians who entered Turkey
did not have passports, denying that they were implicated in the
murder cases.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Foreign Ministry Sunday strongly condemned the arrests of
some Iranian nationals by Turkish police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
