<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Iraqi POWs Return Home From Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Another batch of 460 Iraqi prisoners
of war (POWs), freed by Iran on Tuesday, have arrived in Iraq,
following the release of 480 Iraqi POWs on May 4, the official
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At the Iraqi-Iranian border, hundreds of people, most of them
family members of the POWs, waited to welcome the home-coming POWs.
</P>
<P>
Upon setting foot on the Iraqi soil, many POWs knelt down on the
ground and kissed the soil. They seemed exhausted, but the joyful
reunion with their family members made them in high spirits, the
INA said.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government is making its best efforts to take care of
the returned POWs. After a medical examination, each POW will be
given daily necessities including food and a sum of money for
resettlement, said the INA.
</P>
<P>
It has been reported that Iran will repatriate some 1,000 Iraqi
POWs, in two waves, at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Iran has expressed hope that the unilateral move will help solve
the POWs issue, one of the major hurdles on the way of
normalization of the Tehran-Baghdad ties.
</P>
<P>
Iran released a total of 2,479 Iraqi POWs between April 8 and
May 4, but Iraq says almost 9,000 more are still being held in
Iran, apart from almost 20,000 not registered with the
International Committee of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
According to Baghdad, it holds no more Iranian POWs, but Tehran
says 3,206 Iranian POWs are still held in Iraqi jails.
</P>
<P>
The issue of POWs is a key stumbling block on the way of the
normalization of ties between the two former foes which fought a
bloody war from 1980 to 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
