<HEADLINE> Jordanian House Welcomes "Liberation" of South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's House of Representatives
(lower house of parliament) on Wednesday extended its warmest
congratulations to Lebanon after Israel completely withdrew its
troops from south Lebanon earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
It termed the withdrawal as a liberation of Lebanese territories
and a logical result of the 22-year-long efforts by the Lebanese
people against Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
In a brief statement, the house also called on the international
community to pressure Israel to withdraw its troops from all
occupied Arab territories, including Palestinian lands and the
Golan Heights it captured from Syria during the 1967 Middle East
war, and to recognize an independent Palestinian state with
Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
The statement also reaffirmed Jordan's support for Lebanon to
regain its territories in accordance with U.N. Security Council
Resolution 425, which calls for an immediate and unconditional
Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli forces invaded and occupied southern Lebanon in 1978 and
set up a 850-square-kilometer security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with a self-proclaimed aim to protect its northern borders
from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
Upon an order from Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, the Jewish
state pulled out all its soldiers peacefully from south Lebanon by
Wednesday morning, ahead of its self-imposed deadline of July 7.
</P>
<P>
Most analysts here believe that such an unexpectedly hasty
Israeli troop withdrawal was partly due to mounting casualties
inflicted on Israeli soldiers by guerrilla attacks. Seven Israeli
soldiers have been killed this year during clashes with Lebanese
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The statement also voiced the 80-member house's support for the
efforts by Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein to work on a just,
durable and comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
For years, the kingdom has been a major peace broker between
Israel and its Arab neighbors since it signed a peace treaty with
Israel in 1994, the second Arab country reaching a peace deal with
the Jewish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
