<HEADLINE> Moroccan King Wraps up Official Visit to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Moroccan King Mohammed VI left Cairo
for the Tunisian capital of Tunis on Wednesday, winding up a three-
day official visit to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Mohammed VI held talks with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak on regional issues, particularly Arab cooperation and
solidarity in political and economic spheres.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders co-chaired the fourth session of the Egyptian-
Moroccan Joint Higher Committee, which discussed ways of dealing
with basic shortcomings regarding the balance of trade.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders expressed their countries' readiness to step up
efforts to further enhance bilateral economic and trade cooperation
in a bid to promote the annual trade volume to 100 million U.S.
dollars from the current 37 million dollars, especially after the
signing of the free trade agreement in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Mohammed VI witnessed the signing of six cooperation
agreements Tuesday on the sidelines of the committee meeting. One
of the agreements committed the two countries to expanding the list
of tariff-free goods exchanged within the framework of the free
trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
The rest five agreements cover bilateral cooperation in housing,
environment, quality specifications and other fields.
</P>
<P>
The Moroccan monarch visited Egypt in April to attend the first
Africa-Europe summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
