<HEADLINE> Saddam Receives Letter From Russia on Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
received a letter from his Russian counterpart Vladimir Putin about
the relations between Russia and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The letter was conveyed to the Iraqi president by Nikolai
Khorotzeiv, the visiting special envoy of Russian President
Vladimir Putin, during their meeting held here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The letter touched upon ways to develop the bilateral relations
and promote the long-term friendship between the two countries, the
official Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Putin expressed Russia's stance to continue to
call for the lifting of the U.N. embargo imposed on Iraq since
1990, and extended his personal thanks to the Iraqi president for
congratulating his victory in the Russian presidential election in
March.
</P>
<P>
On March 28, Saddam sent a congratulatory telegram to Vladimir
Putin on his election as the new Russian President, and expressed
the hope that Iraq and Russia can strengthen the existing mutual
friendship and fruitful cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Saddam thanked the Russian president for the
letter, saying Iraq has long been looking for establishing strong
strategic ties with Russia as well as bilateral cooperation in all
fields.
</P>
<P>
Saddam wished Putin success in leading Russia, the INA said.
</P>
<P>
Russia, a close ally and important trade partner of Iraq, has
been calling for the lifting of the embargo on Iraq and the end to
the almost-daily aggressions by U.S. and British warplanes over
northern and southern Iraq since December 1998, when the U.S. and
Britain launched the Operation Desert Fox air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
