<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bahrain, Qatar to Resume Work of Joint Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Bahrain and Qatar agreed in the
Bahraini capital of Manama on Wednesday to resume the work of a
joint committee formed late last year to deal with bilateral issues
including the border dispute between the two Gulf states.
</P>
<P>
"Work of the Joint Supreme Committee will be resumed after the
International Court of Justice made a final ruling over the border
dispute," said a communique issued after talks between Bahraini
Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Issa Al-Khalifa and his visiting Qatari
counterpart Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa Al-Thani in Manama.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hamad Al-Thani went to Bahrain earlier Wednesday, perhaps
in response to calls by Gulf mediators Saudi Arabia and the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) to restore peaceful cooperation in solving
their dispute.
</P>
<P>
Doha and Manama are at present locked in a dispute over several
small but potentially oil-and-gas-rich Gulf isles, including the
Hawar islands, which are controlled by Bahrain since 1930s but also
claimed by Qatar.
</P>
<P>
The issue has been taken to the International Court of Justice
in Hague, the Netherlands, pending a verdict.
</P>
<P>
During the Qatari emir's last visit to Manama in December 1999,
the two Gulf neighbors agreed to set up the supreme committee to
try to settle the border dispute through cordial means.
</P>
<P>
They agreed the case will be withdrawn if an "acceptable
solution is reached by the joint committee before the court's
verdict."
</P>
<P>
But Bahrain announced last Friday that the "work of the
committee has been suspended after Qatar referred the issue to the
Hague international court and that it did not receive any positive
response from Qatar over the recommendations made to solve the
border dispute."
</P>
<P>
Bahrain, which prefers a bilateral compromise solution,
considered the Qatar's reference to the court as stepping over the
mediation efforts by Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates
(UAE).
</P>
<P>
However, a statement by Qatari Foreign Ministry said on Monday
that its demand for the court to resolve the dispute "did not
jeopardize the mediations by Saudi Arabia and the UAE.
</P>
<P>
"Resorting to the International Court of Justice was in line
with the agreements of 1987 and 1990, which was signed by the two
countries as part of the Saudi mediation," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Doha insisted that the "major objective of the committee was not
to solve the border dispute, but really managed to realize many
achievements."
</P>
<P>
Both Saudi Arabia and the UAE have expressed concern over the
new quarrel between Qatar and Bahrain and urged the two small
emirates to resort to peaceful means to overcome their differences.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said that during the meeting, the two
emirs discussed ways of maintaining their solid bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hamad Al-Thani also invited the Bahraini emir to visit
Qatar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Chief Woos Russia As Strategic Partners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Russia and the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) are "strategic partners, not enemies," NATO
Secretary-General George Robertson told a leading Russian
newspaper Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Relations between Russia and the North Atlantic alliance are
steaming ahead and the two sides will continue developing ties
step by step," said Robertson in an exclusive interview with the
Russian newspaper Izvestia on the eve of a meeting of the Russia-
NATO Permanent Joint Council, which started in Italy's resort-city
of Florence Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the work of the council would bring substantial
results of peace and opening a NATO information center in Moscow
will be a very important step for normalizing relations between
Russia and the alliance.
</P>
<P>
NATO adopted a new strategic concept last year and Russia
ratified a new military doctrine early this year. This has caused
some misunderstandings between the two sides, said Robertson,
noting that it makes sense for the two sides to conduct a dialogue,
putting questions to each other.
</P>
<P>
"The more we explain these 'misunderstandings' to each other,
the better we shall strengthen security," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, before attending the Russia-NATO Council
meeting in Florence, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said
Moscow will gradually unfreeze its ties with NATO under the U.N.
Charter and the Russia-NATO Founding Act tenets.
</P>
<P>
Russia's decision to unfreeze relations with NATO coincides
with the interests of European security, he said.
</P>
<P>
An agreement in principle on the opening of a NATO information
bureau in Moscow will be announced at the end of the Russia-NATO
Permanent Council session, the Interfax news agency cited sources
close to Ivanov as saying.
</P>
<P>
Russia and NATO have thus far been at odds over the future
center's status and its tasks. NATO had suggested granting the
center the status of a diplomatic mission, but Russia insists that
its opening be legitimized by letter exchanges between the sides.
</P>
<P>
However, Russian and NATO experts had conducted consultations
on the issue in the run-up to the council session, and a
compromise has probably been reached, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
After NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia last year, Moscow froze
contacts with the alliance and the council sessions have been
suspended for 17 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0028 </DOCNO>
