<HEADLINE> Annan Backs OAU Efforts to Bring Peace to Horn of Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 24 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Wednesday voiced his "strong support" for the diplomatic
efforts by the Organization of African Unity (OAU) to end the
current fighting between Ethiopia and Eritrea, and restore peace
in the Horn of Africa region.
</P>
<P>
A statement, issued here by Annan's spokesman, said, "The
Secretary-General wishes to state his strong support for the
efforts of the Chairman of the OAU, (Algerian) President Abdelaziz
Bouteflika, who is currently in Addis Ababa," capital of Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
"He hopes that President Bouteflika's initiative will swiftly
lead to an end to the fighting, the restoration of the status quo
ante of May 6, 1998, and the resumption of a process which will
bring a lasting end by peaceful means to the current dispute
between Eritrea and Ethiopia," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic efforts to end the border war in the region
intensified Wednesday with both sides urged to withdraw from all
the land seized in two years of fighting.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to increase the diplomatic pressure on both sides,
Bouteflika flew to Addis Ababa Wednesday and officials said he
might travel to Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Both Ethiopia and Eritrea have previously agreed to the idea
of withdrawing troops from occupied territories, declaring a cease-
fire and opening formal talks on fixing their border.
</P>
<P>
But the two countries resumed fighting on May 12 after the
collapse of peace talks in Algeria under the OAU auspices. The two-
year border war has already claimed tens of thousands of lives and
famine threats a combined nine million people in both countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
