<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends UNDOF Mandate Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 24 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Wednesday recommended the extension of the mandate of the
United Nations Disengagement Observer Force (UNDOF) for a further
period of six months until November 30, 2000.
</P>
<P>
In a written report to the United Nations Security Council,
Annan said the situation in the Golan heights continued to be "
potentially dangerous" and would likely remain so until a
comprehensive settlement was reached on all aspects of the Middle
East problems.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the situation in the Force's area of operations
remained quiet over the past six months, although minefields
continue to pose a threat to U.N. personnel and local inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire in the Israeli-Syrian sector held during the
reporting period and the parties continued to cooperate with the
UNDOF, but both sides still denied U.N. inspection teams to some
positions and have restricted the Force's freedom of movement,
Annan said in the report.
</P>
<P>
Drawing attention to the shortfall of some 17 million U.S.
dollars in funding for the Force, Annan appealed to Member States
to pay their assessments and arrears promptly.
</P>
<P>
The UNDOF, which was established in May 1974 to supervise the
cease-fire called for by the Security Council and the agreement on
disengagement between Israeli and Syrian forces of May 31, 1974,
has continued to perform its function effectively, with the
cooperation of the parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
