<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO, Russia Have Frank, Rich Dialogue: Ivanov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FLORENCE, Italy, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov described Wednesday's dialogue with his counterparts
from NATO nations as "frank and rich."
</P>
<P>
Ivanov, who was attending the NATO-Russia Permanent Joint
Council (PJC) at ministerial level, told the press after the
meeting that Wednesday's meeting confirmed the preparedness of
both sides to implement the Founding Act that is of common
interest.
</P>
<P>
The Russian diplomat disclosed that almost all at the table of
Wednesday's PJC spoke in favor of dialogue between NATO and Russia
and of concerted efforts to normalize relations.
</P>
<P>
When asked what can be regarded as a normalized relationship
between the Western military alliance and its former Cold War foe ,
NATO Secretary General George Robertson said that a progress in
the exchange of information for the people on the two sides can be
considered as normal.
</P>
<P>
NATO and Russia discussed and agreed Wednesday to open a NATO
liaison office in Moscow. The opening of the liaison office was
required by the Founding Act that was signed in October 1997 in
Paris. Russia has set up a permanent presence in Brussels, where
the NATO has its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief said that the NATO-Russia relations are the
important core of the Founding Act though the two sides
experienced a "tough year."
</P>
<P>
NATO-Russian ties broke down after the Western military
alliance brushed aside Russian opposition to air strike the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia last year. Russia recalled its
Brussels-based diplomats.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to re-establish relations, Robertson went to
Moscow in February this year and tried to talk Russia back into
dialogue with his institution.
</P>
<P>
The Russian foreign minister, who remained in the government of
newly elected President Vladimir Putin, attributed Russia's slight
of duty to detain the visiting Yugoslav defense minister to a
technical glitch among different government departments.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had already notified the Hague-based
International Tribunal for War Criminals of the former Yugoslavia
and the tribunal had already accepted the explanation.
</P>
<P>
But Ivanov said that he was not satisfied with the performance
of the tribunal and planned to bring the issue up to the United
Nations Security Council for discussion.
</P>
<P>
When asked to pinpoint his dissatisfaction, the Russian foreign
minister said that the tribunal had rather become a political tool
and was not acting objectively in indicting war criminals and even
went it alone in striking a deal with NATO in 1996 on arresting
the indicted.
</P>
<P>
"I do not rule out the possibility of bringing the issue to the
United Nations Security Council," said the Russian through an
interpreter. He cited as examples of prejudice against the Serbs
facts that the lion's share of the indicted war criminals from the
Balkans are Serbs and that most sitting on the Hague tribunal are
from the West and the United States.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the planned communal elections should be
postponed in Kosovo due to the slow return of ethnic Serbs, Ivanov
said that it was a matter of serious concern in that there was not
too much return of non-Albanian refugees to the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
He said that there are now below 100,000 Kosovo Serbs whereas
formally there had been more than 250,000 Serbs in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov accused NATO of lacking the interest in safeguarding the
return of Serbs to Kosovo though NATO foreign ministers promised
Wednesday to act to safeguard the ethnic groups from acts of
violence by Kosovo Albanian extremists.
</P>
<P>
The Russian foreign minister urged full implementation of
United Nations Security Council Resolution 1244 that requires
respect for the territorial integrity and sovereignty of
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
