<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Hails Portugal Decision to Extradite Serial Killer Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 24 (Xinhua) -- France hailed the decision made by
the Supreme Court of Portugal Wednesday to confirm the extradition
toward France of a 20-year-old Frenchman suspect of having killed
three women.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court of Portugal confirmed Wednesday the decision
by an appeal court to extradite Sid Ahmed Rezala, who is suspected
to have killed a British student, a French student and a young
mother from October to December 1999 in France.
</P>
<P>
French Minister of Justice Elisabeth Guigou said that she was
delighted at the decision of the Portuguese Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
However, the extradition can still be delayed by an appeal by
Rezala's lawyer to the Constitutional Tribune of Portugal.
</P>
<P>
Rezala, a French citizen of Algerian origin, is the number one
suspect in the murders of Isabel Peake, Corinne Cailaux and Emilie
Bazin.
</P>
<P>
The body of Peake, a 20-year-old British student, was found by
the side of a railway linking Paris with the central city of
Limoges on October 13, 1999.
</P>
<P>
On December 14, Caillaux, 36, was found killed in the toilet of
a night train when it stopped at the city of Dijon in eastern
France. She was traveling with her four-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
The body of Bazin, a 20-year-old French student, was found in
the cave of a house in Amiens, northern France, on December 17,
after she disappeared for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
The robot-portrait of the suspect made by police corresponds to
the same man who was identified as Rezala by police.
</P>
<P>
In a written interview with the Figaro Magazine earlier this
month, Rezala admitted having killed the three women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
