<HEADLINE> CPLP Defense Ministers Urges for Stiffer Sanctions Against Angolan Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Defense ministers of the member
states of the Community of Portuguese-Speaking Countries (CPLP)
Wednesday expressed their confidence that a stricter UN sanctions
against the Angolan rebels led by Jonas Savimbi will help to end
the Angolan civil war.
</P>
<P>
However, the final declaration of the third CPLP defense
ministers' meeting concluded here Wednesday also voiced concern
over the country's deteriorating humanitarian situation.
</P>
<P>
Defense ministers from Guinea-Bissau, Cape Verde, Mozambique,
Sao Tome and Principe, Portugal and Brazil attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The ministers, at the meeting, unanimously blamed Jonas Savimbi
for the continuation of civil war in Angola, and expressed their
support for international community's stiffer and more effective
sanctions against the Savimbist rebels.
</P>
<P>
They also approved to launch a joint peace keeping oriented
military exercise in Portugal this October or November.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, an observer in the past, officially became a member of
the CPLP defense ministers' cooperation forum during this session.
</P>
<P>
The next CPLP defense ministers' meeting is scheduled for May
21 to 22, 2001 in Brazil, according to the declaration. 
</P>
