<HEADLINE> S. African Police Against Legislation Restricting Their Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Police
Commissioner Jackie Selebi Wednesday said implementing section 49
of the Criminal Procedure Act, which restricts the police's rights
in making arrests, was not suitable for his country on the current
stage.
</P>
<P>
Briefing South African Parliament's select committee on
security, Selebi said section 49 restricted police officers from
defending themselves against armed attacks.
</P>
<P>
Selebi said the fact that a large number of police members had
been killed in the line of duty this year showed the country was
not yet ready for such measures.
</P>
<P>
It was inappropriate to compare South Africa with countries
such as Canada and Sweden, where the rate of violent crime was far
lower, he said.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the South African Human Rights Commission (SAHRC) has
been calling for the promptly taking into effect of the new
section 49. 
</P>
</TEXT>
