<HEADLINE> French Minister Ends Visit to Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 24 (Xinhua) -- French Cooperation Minister Charles
Josselin said in Maputo on Wednesday that France will make efforts
to revive the agreement between the European Union and the ACP
(Africa, Caribbean and Pacific) group countries when it takes over
the EU rotating presidency from July 1.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference at the end of a two day visit
to Mozambique, Josselin said that France would try to persuade
other European countries to take an interest in the southern
hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that all European countries should concern
themselves with Africa", he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He noted that there was great lack of trust between the north
and the south, as exemplified by recent demonstrations in Seattle
and in Washington, against such northern-dominated institutions as
the World Trade Organization, the IMF and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that Europe "has a role to play in restoring this
trust".
</P>
<P>
Josselin also met with Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano,
with whom he discussed bilateral cooperation, the conflicts in the
Great Lakes region, and the situation in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chissano had assured him that the Southern African
Development Community (SADC), which Chissano is currently
chairing, will play an important role in solving the Zimbabwean
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Josselin hoped there would be a speedy return to stability and
peace in Zimbabwe, since the conflict there would also affect its
neighbors. 
</P>
