<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Sets Up Land Compensation Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government on
Wednesday amended the Land Acquisition Act and established a
Compensation Committee to determine the compensation for land
acquired for resettlement.
</P>
<P>
The government said in an extraordinary gazette that the
compensation would be paid for improvements on or to the land.
</P>
<P>
The compensation could be paid in a lump sum, in installments,
in cash, in bonds or other securities issued by the government.
</P>
<P>
The Committee will take into account the age, nature and
condition of the improvements on or to the land, in assessing the
compensation.
</P>
<P>
"Compensation shall be payable for dams, dips, fencing, bore
holes, irrigation equipment," said the government, adding, "in
valuing perennial or plantation crops, regard shall be made to the
potential yield of such crops and their marketability."
</P>
<P>
The compensation will also be paid for any other improvements
on or to the land that have enhanced its value for agricultural
purposes, according to the gazette.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government is under great pressure recently to
start redistributing the land following invasions into white-owned
commercial farms by war veterans during the past months.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe government had already announced that the land
redistribution program would kick off before the country's
parliamentary elections to be held at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
At least 4,500 white farmers own more than 70 percent of arable
land in the southern African country, while majority of the
country's 12.5 million people squashing in other unproductive
land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
