<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets on Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Wednesday met in a closed-door session to discuss the latest
developments in Sierra Leone, where hundreds of U.N. soldiers are
still being held by the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF).
</P>
<P>
The meeting came shortly after U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan promised efforts to get the rest of the detainees into
freedom.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the U.N. Headquarters in New York, Annan
told reporters, "We are all working hard."
</P>
<P>
Liberian President Charles Taylor, who mediated the release of
the detainees, said Wednesday that RUF leader Foday Sankoh, who
currently remains in the custody, needs to be involved in any
negotiation for the release of the detainees.
</P>
<P>
"Let me say that I did speak to President Taylor myself on the
release of the remaining detainees, and we are all working hard,
and, of course, he expects to be able to see some more of the
detainees released before the end of the week," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"There's going to be a meeting in Abuja -- West African heads
of state -- on Saturday," he said. "And of course, I would hope
that, by the time they meet, most of the peacekeepers will be in
freedom."
</P>
<P>
On the bodies that were found in U.N. uniform in bushes in
Sierra Leone, Annan said, "I have not gotten a detailed analysis
as to whether they are really some of our peacekeepers and what
they are, so I would prefer not to comment on that at this stage."
</P>
<P>
Annan, in his written report to the Security Council Monday,
called on the U.N. Mission in Sierra Leone (UNAMSIL) to be
increased by 3,500 to 16,500 military personnel. This is the first
report by Annan on the situation in Sierra Leone since rebels took
U.N. peacekeepers hostage in early May.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council Friday unanimously adopted a resolution to
increase personnel to 13,000.
</P>
<P>
The RUF abducted more than 500 U.N. peacekeepers and civilians
in early May. About 250 U.N. personnel are still being held
hostage in the West African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
