<HEADLINE> India, U.S. Oppose Change in Fiji Government Through Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 24 (Xinhua) -- India and the United States said
Wednesday that they categorically oppose any change in the
government of Fiji through violence, the Press Trust of India (PTI)
reported.
</P>
<P>
The issue of Fijian Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry being
taken hostage by businessman George Speight was discussed during
wide-ranging talks between Indian Foreign Secretary Lalit Mansingh
and visiting U.S. Under Secretary of State for Political Affairs
Thomas Pickering here Wednesday, the PTI reported.
</P>
<P>
New Delhi and Washington maintained that the democratically-
elected government in Fiji should be supported and "changes in
government through violence was no solution of problems," the PTI
said.
</P>
<P>
Mansingh and Pickering were quoted as saying after their
meeting that both of them were in principle against "individuals
being held hostage at gun-point." 
</P>
</TEXT>
