<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Singapore Shares Dip Further on Bleak Prospects  by Wang Xiangjiang, Zhu Changdu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Singapore technology shares
Wednesday further dragged down the broad market for the fifth
consecutive day under double pressure from U.S. interest rates
worries and slack regional markets.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) slipped
33.84 points, or 1.8 percent, to 1,871.94, the lowest in 13 months
and below the 1,900-point psychological barrier.
</P>
<P>
Most other key Asian markets such as Tokyo, South Korea and
Taiwan also retreated after the Dow Jones Average tumbled 120.28
points overnight while the tech-laden Nasdaq fell 5.93 percent to
its lowest level this year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the region will not see a soothing nerve in the
near term as investors are taking cue more from the direction of U.
S.interest rates than from their local economic fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
"The regional sentiment will not possibly be warmed up if there
are no comforting signals coming from the U.S. Federal Reserve,"
said an analyst with a local brokerage.
</P>
<P>
Upcoming U.S. indicators such as average hourly earnings and
payrolls to be released next month are believed to be able to shed
light on the outcome of the Federal Open Market Committee's
meeting in June.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said investors should not worry too much about the
prospect of global stock markets on the back of strong U.S.
economic fundamentals and recovery in European and Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Investors, however, should not expect an excellent performance
on the broad market before 2001, they added.
</P>
<P>
On the Singapore stock market, the electronics index was among
the hardest hit -- down about 15 points in the last five weeks --
as fund managers are retreating from technology counters to blue
chips with strong underlying fundamentals such as Singapore
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said that if the U.S. stock market does not regain at
least some ground, the STI will likely slip further under fund
selling.
</P>
<P>
The STI has shed more than 600 points from the 2,479.58-point
level at the end of 1999 when many analysts predicted a rosy
outlook for Singapore shares to reach a peak as high as 3,000.
</P>
<P>
At present, however, some market watchers began to strike a
relatively pessimistic note, saying the broad market may end up
hovering around the 1,700-point and a major recovery may be seen
not until early next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
