<HEADLINE> Senegal to Continue Cooperation With France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Senegalese President Abdoulaye Wade
said here on Wednesday that the new government of Senegal will
maintain its traditional cooperation with France.
</P>
<P>
Wade, who is on a visit to France until May 28, made the
remarks after a dinner with French President Jacques Chirac at the
Elysee presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the visit is to seek more efficient cooperation
between Senegal and France in all fields as well as more private
investment by French enterprises in Senegal, said Senegalese
officials.
</P>
<P>
Wade took over power in Senegal on March 19 after defeating his
rival, President Abdou Diouf, in the elections.
</P>
<P>
France, which is the biggest donor country of Senegal with an
annual public aid package of 840 million francs (110 million U.S.
dollars), is bidding for new projects in Senegal, including the
construction of a new international airport in Dakar, the
repairing of the railway between Dakar and Bamako in Mali and the
building of new hospitals.
</P>
<P>
France is also the biggest trade partner of Senegal, with the
export to the country reaching 2.9 billion francs (310 million U.S.
dollars) and the import from it hitting 791 million francs (110
million U.S. dollars) last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
