<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Ready to Join U.N. Peacekeeping in Lebanon: Jospin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 24 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
said on Wednesday that France is ready to take its responsibility
in the United Nations peacekeeping force to be deployed in
southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But Jospin said that the U.N. must obtain "concrete commitment"
from all the three countries involved in the conflict -- Israel,
Syria and Lebanon -- on providing indispensable security
guarantees for the peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
When answering questions at the National Assembly, Jospin said
that if the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFL) is to
be re-deployed, it should be done in a very short period of time.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the ultimate objective of the mission will be
to help the Lebanese government restore its authority in the
former Israeli-imposed security zone.
</P>
<P>
Israel announced on Wednesday that its troops have completed
pullout from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
France has 250 soldiers participating in the UNIFL, which is
expected to be reinforced from the present 4,500 men to 7,935 when
it is re-deployed.
</P>
<P>
"If all the conditions are met, (U.N. Secretary-General) Kofi
Annan knows that he can count on the determination of France to
engage itself in serving the cause of a lasting peace in the
region," said Jospin.
</P>
<P>
He said that Annan should first "certify" that Israel has
pulled out of troops in conformity with the U.N. Resolution 425,
before the UNIFL is re-deployed.
</P>
<P>
"Before engaging ourselves on this road, we will study the
situation in the field and the guarantees that all the sides are
ready to give," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
