<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Minority Groups Vulnerable to Violence: NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FLORENCE, Italy, May 24 (Xinhua) -- NATO on Wednesday admitted
that minority groups in Kosovo remain vulnerable to acts of
violence by Albanian extremists.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the 19 NATO member states concluded
after their council meeting that the protection of ethnic groups
and minorities in the Yugoslav province is still the most
challenging issue for the NATO-led peacekeeping force (KFOR) and
the United Nations Mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that between 80,000 and 100,000 Kosovo Serbs
stayed in Kosovo after the 78-day NATO air strikes last year that
aimed at forcing the Serbian security forces out of the province.
Kosovo Albanians have been the ethnic majority in the province.
</P>
<P>
"We condemn all acts of violence, be they ethnically,
politically or criminally motivated," the NATO foreign ministers
concluded.
</P>
<P>
"We commend KFOR's robust actions to deal with extremists from
all sides and provide security and protection to members of all
ethnic groups and minorities," the ministers added.
</P>
<P>
The western military alliance also expressed support for the U.
N. Mission in Kosovo (UNMIK) to intensify its fight against
organized crimes, arms trafficking, illegal possession of weapons
and trafficking in women.
</P>
<P>
Most of these crimes are reported to be linked with Albanian
extremists.
</P>
<P>
"We commend KFOR and UNMIK for progress achieved in their joint
efforts to promote co-existence in a united and secure Mitrovica,"
said the foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
Mitrovica, a town in northern Kosovo, was once a flare-up point
of inter-ethnic tensions.
</P>
<P>
NATO also expressed concerns about continued violence and
instability in the area adjacent to the internal boundary between
Kosovo and Serbia.
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers said that KFOR will act firmly against
those who wish to use Kosovo as a base from which to export
violence.
</P>
<P>
"We regard any unrest or instability in these areas as a threat
to our efforts to establish peace and stability throughout the
region," it said.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo Albanians have allegedly sneaked across the internal
boundary into Serbia to stir instability on the other side by
fermenting ethnic hatred among local Albanian residents and by
smuggling weapons there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missile System More for American Dominance: Canadian Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The controversial ballistic missile
defense system being proposed by the United State is more about
solidifying American power than about protecting against "rogue
nations," Canadian military planners say.
</P>
<P>
The Ottawa Citizen newspaper reported Wednesday that the
country's Department of National Defense policy officials believe
the threat posed by the so-called "rogue nations" is secondary to
the main aim of ballistic missile defense.
</P>
<P>
"Arguably (it is) more in order to preserve U.S./NATO freedom
of action," the newspaper quoted briefing documents prepared for a
closed-door military meeting in November in Ottawa as saying.
</P>
<P>
The briefing notes also point out that the U.S. will have
trouble getting all its allies on side to support a missile system
to protect North America, as there is concern that the shield will
violate existing arms treaties with the Russians.
</P>
<P>
The documents suggest that Canadian participation in the
national missile shield is more about maintaining good relations
with the U.S. than it is about protecting Canada.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations are under way to assign senior Canadian officers
to the U.S. Ballistic Missile Defense Organization in Washington,
said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Art Eggleton and military officials continue
to hold that the Canadian forces is doing no work, beyond basic
research and information gathering, on the American missile shield.
</P>
<P>
They insist no decision has been officially made by the
Canadian government about whether to sign on to the American
scheme, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
