<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, May 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Santiago Appeals Court took away parliamentary
immunity from life-long senator Augusto Pinochet, reported Tuesday
Chilean electronic paper, "The Counter".
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted judicial sources and others close to the
government as saying that "Pinochet was deprived of rights by 12
votes againt 10." (Chile-Pinochet-Immunity)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands -- After a 12-day adjournment and then
a 24-hour pause, prosecutors Wednesday resumed to build their case
against two Libyans suspected in the bombing of a Pan Am flight in
1988.
</P>
<P>
Testimony on Wednesday morning focused on how aircraft debris
had been found, collected and labeled at a purpose-built warehouse
near the crash site.
</P>
<P>
In cross examination, the defense team got policemen witnesses
to admit that labels on various pieces of evidence had been
changed from time to time.
</P>
<P>
The 12-day court adjournment allowed prosecutors time to cancel
as many as 230 witnesses scheduled to testify about the recovery
of some 40,000 pieces of evidence from around 1,200 square
kilometers. (Lockerby-Trial-Resume)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said on Wednesday
that France is ready to take its responsibility in the United
Nations peacekeeping force to be deployed in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But Jospin said that the U.N. must obtain "concrete commitment"
from all the three countries involved in the conflict -- Israel,
Syria and Lebanon -- on providing indispensable security
guarantees for the peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
Jospin said that if the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon
(UNIFL) is to be re-deployed, it should be done in a very short
period of time. (France-Lebanon-U.N.) 
</P>
</TEXT>
