<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wuhan Improves Investment Climate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Two hundred delegates from United
Nations organizations, foreign government missions, international
consortia and multinationals today attended a fund-raiser here to
secure funding for sustainable development projects.
</P>
<P>
The event is part of the ongoing sustainable development
management program in Wuhan, in central China's Hubei province,
which receives aid from United Nations Development Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
The scheme has been implemented in this central China city for
three years.
</P>
<P>
Today's gathering was designed to raise 8.3 billion yuan (about
one billion U.S. dollars) for building in the city 27 major
sustainable development projects in four areas -- environmental
protection, harnessing of ground water pollution, air pollution,
and garbage treatment.
</P>
<P>
Douglas McCallum, an expert with U.N. Center for Human
Settlements (UNCHS), said he was pleased to see Wuhan's
development project had matured so well in the three years it has
been in effect.
</P>
<P>
He said the Sustainable Cities Program (SCP), a program for
demonstrating technical aid, jointly promoted by UNCHS and the U.N.
Environmental Program (UNEP) since 1996, has been carried out in
more than 30 cities around the world, including Wuhan and Shenyang
of northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
SCP wants to put sustainable development strategy in place in
cities worldwide by stepping up environmental control, and
coordinating the relationship between environmental and economic
development in these places.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Boost Natural Gas Development in 21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese oil expert has
predicted China's proven gas reserve will increase by an annual
average of 120 billion cu m between 2001 and 2020, with gas
utilization accounting for eight percent of China's energy
consumption instead of the present two percent.
</P>
<P>
Wu Yaowen, vice-president of the China National Petroleum Corp.
(CNPC), said here today that the country's annual gas output will
hit anything between 110 billion cu m and 130 billion cu m in the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
And by 2020, China will produce 100 billion cubic meters of gas,
equivalent to 100 million tons of crude oil.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the on-going seminar on China's energy development
strategy in the 21st century, Wu said that China will give
priority to the development of natural gas in its energy strategy
in the 21st century, which will be concentrated in the rich gas-
bearing regions in the western parts of the country, including the
Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia region, Sichuan province and the Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia Basin in northwest China, the site of
China's largest gas field, has so far verified gas reserves of
nearly 309.8 billion cu, ranking among the world's 80 largest gas
fields.
</P>
<P>
About 100 billion cubic meters of gas reserves have been proven
in the eastern part of southwest China's Sichuan province, which
shows the enormous potential for further gas exploration.
</P>
<P>
And large gas production bases are taking shape in the basins
of Turpan-Hami, Junggar and Tarim in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
According to Wu, China will speed up construction of gas
pipelines in both western and eastern China, which extend from gas
production bases in western China to the economically developed
regions of North China, Northeast China, and the delta areas of
the Yangtze River and the Pearl River.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
