<HEADLINE> Morgan Stanley: Cheung Kong Represents Outstanding Value </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Leading global investment bank
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Wednesday reiterated its positive view
on Cheung Kong Holdings as a high-value stock, despite the company
's recent removal from the MSCI Hong Kong Index.
</P>
<P>
Peter Churchouse, managing director and co-head of Asian
Research at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said: "MSCI's decision to
drop Cheung Kong from its Hong Kong index was a surprise to many
investors and observes, including ourselves."
</P>
<P>
"In our view the company represents an excellent value
opportunity and should remain a core holding for fund managers in
its own right, not least because of Cheung Kong's outstanding
management, excellent growth prospects, leadership in the property
industry and its exposure to Hutchison," said Churchouse.
</P>
<P>
"Cheung Kong makes real money and has consistently delivered
outstanding shareholder value. At the same time its stock is among
the most liquid in the Hong Kong market. For all these reasons we
retain our market 'outperform' rating on Cheung Kong with a target
price for the stock of 110 HK dollars (14.1 U.S. dollars) on a 12-
month time horizon," he said.
</P>
<P>
John W. Wadsworth, chairman of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Asia,
echoed Churchouse's view. He said Cheung Kong Chairman Li Ka-shing
is clearly among the world's outstanding business leaders and an
increasingly powerful force in business globally who has created
enormous value for shareholders over the years.
</P>
<P>
"It is important to remember that MSCI's role as an index
provider is categorically not to make qualitative judgments on
companies. MSCI's removal of Cheung Kong from its Hong Kong index
is in no way a comment on its quality as a company, which, clearly
is one of Asia's leaders," he concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
