<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Top Prosecutor Closes Weizman's File </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Israel's top prosecutor decided
Wednesday not to file criminal charges against President Ezer
Weizman for accepting cash gifts from a French businessman.
</P>
<P>
But Weizman had clearly committed violations of ethical rules
applying to senior civil servants which could, in the future cases,
be considered as criminal acts, Attorney General Elyakim Rubinstein
said in a broadcast statement.
</P>
<P>
The long-awaited decision was contained in a 60-page document
which included Rubinstein's formal decision and State Attorney Edna
Arbel's examination of the allegations and the reasoning behind her
decision to close the file.
</P>
<P>
"The opinion focuses on the question of whether there is room to
establish a criminal trial, and at this level our response is
negative," the decision added.
</P>
<P>
Police launched investigations against Weizman in January after
local media disclosed that Weizman, while serving as a lawmaker and
cabinet minister from 1988 to 1993, had accepted more than 300,000
U.S. dollars from French millionaire Edouard Saroussi.
</P>
<P>
Police investigated Weizman on allegations of bribery taking,
fraud and breach of faith, breaking the law barring civil servants
from accepting gifts and income tax violations.
</P>
<P>
Rubinstein said there was no doubt Weizman had broken the rules
banning senior public servants from receiving income other than
their salaries and stipulating that they must report their income
to the State Comptroller.
</P>
<P>
Weizman's violation of these rules fell short of a criminal act,
Rubinstein said, but he warned that such a behavior in the future
by a senior civil servant could warrant criminal prosecution on
charges of breach of faith.
</P>
<P>
Early in the day, Weizman said he was pleased that the case had
been closed and that as far as he was concerned, "the matter is
finished and done with."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that he planned to step down by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
"I will consult with my family and the prime minister and decide
on the exact date," he added.
</P>
<P>
Weizman, 76 and in failing health, is serving his second five-
year term, due to expire in 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Welcomes Israeli Pullout From South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait on Wednesday welcomed the
just-completed Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon, saying it has
been following the movement with satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
"Kuwait welcomes this withdrawal and calls for Israel to
complete the pullback from all Lebanese territories to the
internationally recognized border," said Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah,
Kuwaiti First Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister, in a
statement to Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He praised the efforts exerted by United Nations Secretary-
General Kofi Annan in securing the Israeli withdrawal on the basis
of U.N. Security Council Resolution 425, which calls for an
immediate and unconditional Israeli pullout from all Lebanese
territory and for a return of full sovereignty to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel invaded and occupied south Lebanon in 1978 and set up a
so-called security zone there in 1985 with a self-claimed aim of
protecting its northern settlements from cross-border guerrilla
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Israel began to withdraw its troops from south Lebanon earlier
this month. It had promised to complete the military pullback by
July.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti official voiced hope for the "continuation of
efforts aimed at making the Middle East peace process a success on
all tracks and at attaining complete Israeli withdrawal from all
Arab territories including Syria's Golan Heights."
</P>
<P>
He urged Israel to cease attacks on Lebanese civilians and
release all Lebanese prisoners in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
Israel concluded its hasty full-scale withdrawal from south
Lebanon early Wednesday, ending its 22 years of occupation of the
Lebanese territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
