<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, US Vow Not to Support Tamil State in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 24 (Xinhua) -- India and the United States
Wednesday ruled out support for any independent Tamil state
carved out of Sri Lanka and said there was no military solution
possible to the ethnic strife on the island nation, the Press
Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. does not support any kind of independent state in Sri
Lanka," U.S. Under Secretary of State for Political Affairs Thomas
Pickering was quoted as saying here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Indian Foreign Secretary Lalit Mansingh echoed by saying: "That
remains our position too."
</P>
<P>
Pickering, who arrived here Tuesday night on a two-day visit to
India, met Indian Defense Minister George Fernandes and Foreign
Secretary Mansingh Wednesday. His visit is part of regular foreign
office exchanges on Asian security initiated during U.S. President
Bill Clinton's visit to India in March.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting the possibility of any military solution, Pickering
said Washington supports any constructive role by India in Sri
Lanka, the PTI reported.
</P>
<P>
According to Pickering, the United States is watching the
situation in Sri Lanka carefully and supporting the Norwegian role
to broker peace.
</P>
<P>
Everything must be done to avert a humanitarian catastrophe in
Jaffna peninsula, said Pickering, who stressed, "Humanitarian
considerations are paramount in the current situation to avoid
innocent civilians being caught in crossfire."
</P>
<P>
Both New Delhi and Washington made it clear that they favor a
peaceful settlement in Jaffna keeping in view the aspirations of
all communities on the island, the PTI said.
</P>
<P>
Both Pickering and Mansingh also noted that Washington and New
Delhi had nothing to do with the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
(LTTE), which has been declared a terrorist organization by the
United States and is banned in India.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting for an independent Tamil state in
the east and north of Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Mansingh restated the Indian government's stand that New Delhi
"would be willing to extend humanitarian aid if sought" by Colombo,
adding that so far there has been no request from Colombo in this
regard.
</P>
<P>
He also parried all questions on preparations by the Indian
Armed Forces regarding possible evacuation of Sri Lankan troops
trapped in Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
Pickering, who is expected to meet Indian National Security
Advisor Brajesh Mishra and Opposition leader Sonia Gandhi on
Thursday, will fly to Pakistan Thursday evening and then travel to
Colombo for talks with the Sri Lankan authorities, the PTI
reported. 
</P>
