<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria Causes Some 20 percent Death in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Statistics indicate that malaria has
led to between 12 and 20 percent of health facility deaths in
Zambia, health minister David Mpamba said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mpamba told Roll Back Malaria Stakeholders Meeting that in
Zambia malaria is the leading cause of ill health and death. It
accounts for 30 percent of all health centre and hospital
admissions.
</P>
<P>
He demanded new, cost-effective strategies to fight the scourge
in his country where the resources for malaria prevention and
control have unfortunately dwindled.
</P>
<P>
He urged the participants of the meeting to identify and put
into place innovative, promotive, preventive and curative
strategies to effectively reduce the impact of the malaria on
Zambians.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government is committed to the globally recognized
initiative for rolling back malaria by significantly reducing
morbidity especially in under-fives and in pregnancy, Mpamba said.
</P>
</TEXT>
