<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockerbie Trial Resumes After 24-hour Pause </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands, May 24 (Xinhua) -- After a 12-day
adjournment and then a 24-hour pause, prosecutors Wednesday
resumed to build their case against two Libyans suspected in the
bombing of a Pan Am flight in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Testimony on Wednesday morning focused on how aircraft debris
had been found, collected and labeled at a purpose-built warehouse
near the crash site.
</P>
<P>
In cross examination, the defense team got policemen witnesses
to admit that labels on various pieces of evidence had been
changed from time to time.
</P>
<P>
The defense team was trying to cast doubt on the case the
prosecution was trying to build. Under Scottish Law, the
prosecution bears the burden of proof and has to prove its case "
beyond reasonable doubt" before the judges give their verdict.
</P>
<P>
Libyans Abdel Basset al-Megrahi and Al-Amin Khalifa Fahima were
accused of conspiracy to murder and breaching the international
aircraft safety act.
</P>
<P>
The court, which was built in a former United States air force
base in central Netherlands, had to be adjourned for 12 days after
an out-of-the-court agreement was struck between the prosecution
and the defense team to skip time-consuming court hearings on
undisputed facts.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutors were given extra time to reorganize their case
so that the court upon resumption could focus directly on the
cause of the mid-air explosion that killed 259 people aboard the
Boeing-747 jet airliner and another 11 on the ground.
</P>
<P>
A technical glitch Tuesday, however, on the in-court
computerized stenography system forced the Scottish judges to
adjourn the trial for another 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
The 12-day court adjournment allowed prosecutors time to cancel
as many as 230 witnesses scheduled to testify about the recovery
of some 40,000 pieces of evidence from around 1,200 square
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The long-awaited Lockerbie trial is now expected to last up to
a year's time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
