<HEADLINE> China Opens Website On World Heritage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, May 24 (Xinhua) -- China's first website on the country
's most famous cultural and natural spots was opened today.
</P>
<P>
Available at www.cnwh.org is the latest information on world
heritage sites such as the Great Wall, the Imperial Palace in the
Forbidden City and the Wuyishan Mountain.
</P>
<P>
The website also includes columns on current issues in world
heritage work, a relics protection hotline, tourism, laws and
codes and a chat room, said Lu Xiaochuan, general manager of the
Suzhou Yuanjing Information Company which sponsors the website.
</P>
<P>
The new website, in both Chinese and English, has links to
related international websites.
</P>
<P>
China signed the Convention Concerning the Protection of the
World Cultural and Natural Heritage in 1985. So far, 23 cultural
and natural sites in China have been included on the World
Heritage list.  
</P>
</TEXT>
