<HEADLINE> Mainland Taiwanese Support Statement (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chen Guizhou, vice-president of the All-China Federation of
Taiwan Compatriots, said that in his May 20 inauguration speech,
the Taiwan new leader evaded the major issues and described one-
China as something that would happen in the future.
</P>
<P>
It is hard to believe that the new leader is willing to accept
the one-China principle and that he sincerely wants to ease the
cross-Straits relations, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Honorary Chairman Cai Zimin of the Central Committee of Taiwan
Democratic Self-Government League said that if the new leader of
Taiwan is sincere in adopting a conciliatory stance in regard to
the cross-Straits relations, he should recognize the one-China
principle.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the forum also noted that the two sides of the
Taiwan Straits have been separated for 50 years and that the issue
of Taiwan should not drag on forever.
</P>
<P>
If the new leader of Taiwan is serious about maintaining the
happiness of people on both sides of the Straits, and the peace
and stability of the cross-Straits relations, he should revert to
the one-China stance.
</P>
<P>
Issues of democracy, freedom and human rights are excuses used
by the Taiwan leaders to block the peaceful reunification of the
motherland, they said, adding that recognition of the one-China
principle and peaceful reunification are the only way out for the
island of Taiwan. 
</P>
