<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syria and Japan signed on Tuesday an agreement under
which Japan will offer 6 million U.S. dollars of grant to finance a
project to increase food production in Syria.
</P>
<P>
The grant will be used for the purchase of tractors and other
farming equipments to be distributed among Syrian farmers.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Iran are studying the construction of five
factories for the production of cane sugar in Tehran at an
estimated cost of 150 million dollars to be slashed off Egypt's
debts to Iran.
</P>
<P>
Iran's investments in Egypt are estimated at 85 million dollars,
mainly in textile, artificial silk and ready-made wear. The total
value of trade exchange between the two countries stood at 80
million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish brokerage house Global Securities brokered a
takeover by U.S. food maker Bestfoods of Egypt's EL-Rashidi EL
Mizan Confectionary.
</P>
<P>
Bestfoods paid approximately 19.5 million dollars for a 51-
percent stake in EL Rashidi, whereby it earned a foothold in the
Egyptian food market. The deal also allows Bestfoods to take up
another 34 percent stake in the company by 2002.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Leading Swedish food packager Tetra Pak plans to
expand its operations in Turkey by entering the plastic packaging
sector.
</P>
<P>
Tetra Pak has been producing cardboard packaging for pasteurized
milk and other food products in Turkey for 14 years, said Tetra Pak
Turkey General Manager Jan Hildingstam in Istanbul Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In addition to its ongoing liquid food processing and cardboard
packaging operations, the company is now planning to supply PET
manufacturing equipment.
</P>
<P>
Tetra Pak increased its business volume in Turkey by 15 percent
in 1999 as compared to the previous year, and sales to 90 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Turkish Treasury has accepted to stand as
guarantor for 379 million dollars in foreign loans which will be
used to finance a coal-fired power plant in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The plant will be financed through export loans from France,
Germany, Spain, and commercial loans from Credit Agricole Indosuez.
Hungary is also extending export and commercial loans.
</P>
<P>
The power plant will burn around 1.75 million tons of coal a
year and generate 2 billion kilowatt-hours of electricity annually.
The first unit of the plant must be completed in 34 months and the
plant is scheduled to be fully operational May 2003, when the
second unit will be delivered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
