<HEADLINE> Iran's Conservative Parliament Bids Farewell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran's fifth Majlis (parliament),
dominated by the right wing conservatives, was officially concluded
on Wednesday after closing its last session.
</P>
<P>
Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq Nouri presented a full report on the
performance of the fifth parliament before ringing a bell to
announce the end of its term.
</P>
<P>
The sixth parliament, elected in February with reformers seizing
most of the 290 seats, is scheduled to convene on Saturday, the
official Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
With reformers controlling the new parliament, it is expected
that President Mohammad Khatami's social and political reform
programs, mostly stymied by the fifth parliament, will be given a
powerful push.
</P>
<P>
For the reformers, however, the victory has been costly. They
had to see their activists being summoned by court and imprisoned
and their newspapers banned in the months following the February
elections.
</P>
<P>
As the top supervisor of the election, the conservative
Guardians Council only approved the election result in the Tehran
constituency last Saturday, after a delay of nearly three months.
Tehran is the reformists' most important political base, where
reformers won at least 26 of the 30 seats.
</P>
<P>
The Guardians deprived some reformist winners of their victory,
transferring their seats to conservative opponents. Even now, only
a few days ahead of the inauguration of the new parliament, it is
still holding up the election results in a number of
constituencies.
</P>
<P>
Facing the relentless conservative crackdown, Khatami, who
launched the country's reformist campaign after he took up the
presidency in 1997, has told his allies to keep calm and be
tolerant.
</P>
<P>
The most important thing was to guarantee the opening of the
news parliament in due time, he said, warning that radical moves by
the reformers might spark tougher crackdown by the conservatives
hardliners, who still have grip of most of the state powers.
</P>
<P>
With the reformers starting to carry out their duties in the new
parliament, and the next presidential election to be held in 2001,
the political struggle between conservatives and reformists enters
a new phase yet to be defined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
