<HEADLINE> ASEAN Wants US to Normalize Trade With All Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 24 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN Wednesday called on the
United States to normalize trade relations with all its member
countries to further boost the development of the region which is
fast recovering from the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Foreign Ministry Secretary-General Abdul Kadir
Mohamed made the call at a two-day ASEAN-U.S. dialogue which began
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia wishes to highlight once again the absence of
development cooperation programs in the U.S.-ASEAN dialogue
relations and the fact that the United States still does not have
normal trade relations with some ASEAN member countries, Abdul
Kadir, co-chairman and country coordinator for the dialogue, said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN would like to reiterate its call on the United States to
review its policy in this regard, Abdul Kadir said, adding that as
an economic superpower, the United States is a major market for
ASEAN products and an important source of foreign direct
investment.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN hopes that U.S. policy would give support to sustain and
strengthen the growth and development in this region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Co-chairman Ralph L. Boyce, U.S. deputy assistant secretary of
state for East Asia and Pacific affairs, said at the opening that
his country shared ASEAN's wish that the relationship between the
dialogue partners continue to be strong and vibrant.
</P>
<P>
"The ASEAN region and its 10 member nations are very important
to the US," he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar,the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
