<HEADLINE> Mozambican Court Grants Bail to Renamo Delegate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The court in the northern Mozambican
province of Nampula has granted bail to Alvaro Chale, the
political delegate of the former rebel movement Renamo in the
district of Angoche, who has been in detention since Monday last
week.
</P>
<P>
Chale is accused of involvement in the May 5 attack on the
police station in Aube, in which the police commander was
seriously injured, and four of the attackers were shot dead in
what the police described as legitimate self-defense.
</P>
<P>
Cited in Wednesday's issue of the daily paper "Noticias", one
of Chale's lawyers, Antonio Feliciano, said that his client has
only to pay the bail determined by the court to await trial in
freedom.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to the court's decision, another of Chale's defense
team, Maximo Dias, who is also a parliamentary deputy for the
Renamo-Electoral Union coalition, said that the judge "was right"
to grant bail to Chale and let him await trial in provisional
freedom while the Criminal Investigation Police is still doing its
job.
</P>
<P>
Dias said that Chale will continue to lead his normal life,
and will maintain his post as Renamo political delegate in
Angoche.
</P>
<P>
Chale is accused of participation in incitement to violence and
public disorder on May 5.
</P>
<P>
He denies all the accusations, arguing that on that date he was
in Maputo, on holiday.
</P>
<P>
A team of high ranking Renamo officials, led by Ossufo Quitine,
head of the Renamo parliamentary group, is to visit Aube to learn
at first hand what led to the detention of their delegate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
