<HEADLINE> France, U.S. Discuss U.N. Peacekeeping Mission in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 24 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright discussed
the U.N. peacekeeping mission in Lebanon on Wednesday at a meeting
of NATO foreign ministers in Florence, Italy.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret said
that Vedrine explained to Albright the conditions needed for
France to join such a mission.
</P>
<P>
France and other countries which are expected to join the
mission must have the full support from four other permanent
members of the U.N. Security Council, said the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. force in Lebanon should not be condemned to "a passive
and impotent witness" in the face of a deteriorating situation,
and its organizational and commanding structure as well as its
mandate must be clear, she said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the three countries involved in the conflict in
Lebanon -- Israel, Syria and Lebanon -- should behave in a
responsible way in a new situation after the pullout of Israeli
troops, she added.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine and Albright also agreed to reinforce cooperation
between France and the United States in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac said on Tuesday that France
will study in "an open and comprehensive way" any demand for its
contribution to the U.N. peacekeeping operation in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
France has 250 soldiers in the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (
UNIFL), which has been deployed there since 1978.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan has suggested that UNIFL
be reinforced from 4,500 members to 7,935 when it is redeployed in
the areas of Lebanon evacuated by the Israelis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
