<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Aviation Conference Opens in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The International Air Transport
Association (IATA) Millennium Asia and Pacific Regional Technical
Conference opened here Wednesday, attracting over 120
representatives from airlines, international and airline
organizations, the aviation industry and air traffic services
providers.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference is held in two parts. The first is a
business session to meet the governance requirements, and the
second is a symposium, with the theme topic of "Exploitation of
the Capabilities of Modern Transport Aircraft," exploring the
capability of modern aircraft to enhance safety and increase
operational efficiency.
</P>
<P>
"Many airline operators have upgraded their fleets to enable
advantage to be taken of the operational and safety improvements
offered by the Satellite-Based Communications, Navigation and
Surveillance/Air Traffic Management (CNS/ATM) Systems." said
Albert Lam, Director of Hong Kong Civil Aviation, at the opening
ceremony of the conference.
</P>
<P>
"To achieve the maximum benefit of these capabilities, it is
clearly essential that the enhancements provided by the
manufacturers and funded by the operators are matched in tandem by
air traffic control authorities through the timely provision of up-
to-date air route systems, associated infrastructure and the
corresponding ground elements of CNS/ATM," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Through the strenuous efforts of the International Civil
Aviation Organisation (ICAO), IATA, the airline operators and air
traffic services providers, various trials on the CNS/ATM systems
have been conducted." Lam said.
</P>
<P>
The CNS/ATM systems will minimize airspace constraints and
reduce traffic congestion, which will enable aircraft to operate
within their most optimum flight envelope, commensurate with
achieving a marked increase in flight safety.
</P>
<P>
In addition, by operating on more direct routes, a reduction in
aircraft fuel consumption is also feasible.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Civil Aviation Department is now conducting a study
and trial of the system for implementation and transition in 2003-
2016, according to Lam.
</P>
<P>
Lam also urged the attendees of the conference to give support
and encouragement in maintaining the present momentum to achieve a
safe, economic and expeditious movement of aircraft around the
world.
</P>
<P>
"We will fully support this aim and are committed to maintain
Hong Kong as a regional and international aviation center," he
added.
</P>
<P>
IATA requires that technical conference are held at two yearly
intervals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Stocks Close Below 14,000-Mark Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks lost a sizable
323.20 points to close below the 14,000-mark level at 13,933.98
Wednesday, dragged down by tech-led decline as traders followed U.
S. investors to pull out of tech stocks.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq dived 5.93 percent to 3,164.55, its fifth straight
session down, on Tuesday as investors judged tech stocks
overvalued and likely to be more vulnerable to further interest
rates rises.
</P>
<P>
Local tech stocks are also viewed as overvalued, which
triggered further declines of their prices, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
HSI heavyweight China Telecom lost 4.68 percent to 47.90 HK
dollars. Other Telecom stocks followed suit, with Hutchison
Whampoa dropping 2.21 percent to 88.5 HK dollars, Pacific Century
CyberWorks falling 3.13 percent to 13.95 HK dollars, and Cable and
Wireless HKT losing 1.11 percent to 17.75 HK dollars.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong stocks suffered an across-the-board declines on
Wednesday, with all the indices registering losses, on a turnover
of 9.168 billion HK dollars (1.175 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The four sub-indices of Hang Seng Index, namely, Finance,
Utilities, Properties and Commerce and Industry, lost by 1.24
percent, 0.56 percent, 2.37 percent and 2.97 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index and the Hang Seng China-
Affiliated Corp Index lost a further 3.04 percent and 3.09 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng IT Index fell 3.97 percent to close at 2,483.49,
and the Hang Seng IT Portfolio Index lost 4.23 percent to end at 3,
225.93.  
</P>
</TEXT>
