<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intel Chief Sees Rosy Future of Asia's Digital Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Intel Corporation's President and
CEO Craig R. Barrett said here Wednesday that China's entry into
the World Trade Organization (WTO) is good for U.S. companies to
continue their business in China.
</P>
<P>
"China's becoming a member of the WTO and being granted the
permanent normal trade relations (PNTR) status mean that we will
continue to do business in China as we have," he told the press.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives is due to vote on the PNTR
issue Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Barrett expected China to overtake Japan to become the second
largest PC consumer nation later this year or earlier next year.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward to continuing stronger growth in China,
" said the head of the world's largest chip maker.
</P>
<P>
Barrett also foresaw an enormous growth in digital economy in
Asia as a whole, quoting the figures provided by the Garner Group
in January 2000 that the Asian market is expected to account for
14 percent of the world's business-to-business e-commerce, growing
at an estimated rate of 150 percent through 2004.
</P>
<P>
The business-to-business e-commerce worldwide is expected to
grow to 7 trillion U.S. dollars in the next four years and the
business-to-business sales in Asia, excluding Japan, will reach 1
trillion U.S. dollars within the next five years, said Barrett.
</P>
<P>
Barrett is in Hong Kong, Intel's Asia Pacific headquarters, for
the Third Digital Economy Forum and the signing of a memorandum of
understanding with Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT on accelerating e-business
in Hong Kong and the rest of the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
At Wednesday's session of the forum, Barrett called on
businesses to increase efficiency through the use of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
"Successful companies will be the ones who become 100 percent e-
business by integrating all aspects of their business from
internal customers, external customers and suppliers, partners and
affiliates in an e-business environment," Barrett said.
</P>
<P>
He thought more electronic transactions equal more business
advantages.
</P>
<P>
"By converting more interactions with your customers, suppliers,
employees and partners into electronic business transactions, you
can build a more efficient and competitive business," he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that with the Internet as the driving force
behind the dramatic changes in business today, Hong Kong will see
an exponential growth in the Internet economy.
</P>
<P>
"Backed by strong infrastructure investments, low connection
costs and government support to boost PC and Internet penetration,
Hong Kong can become the Internet leader in Asia Pacific," Barrett
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
