<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Asian Firms Urged to Take Lead in Digital Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Enterprises in Asia were urged to
be bold in decision-making and responsive to the fast-moving
opportunities ahead as the Internet is now reshaping and
redefining virtually every aspect of communications and
transactions in the region, participants in a forum on the digital
economy said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 250 top corporate executives in Asia gathered in Hong
Kong from May 22-24 for the third annual digital economy forum in
an attempt to find answers to how to cope with the bewildered e-
commerce and its rampant development.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the three-day event with the theme of "
Convergent Leadership: Putting Ideas to Work" focused their
discussions on prevailing and developing business issues Asian
companies must consider in meeting the challenges of competing in
the digital economy.
</P>
<P>
In his opening remarks, Charles Wang, chairman and CEO of the U.
S. Computer Association International Inc. and honorary chairman
of the forum, said, "The Internet has captured our imagination by
transforming monumentally challenging tasks that were costly and
difficult to implement into an ubiquitous medium that is easily
accessible by anyone at anytime."
</P>
<P>
Competing in the digital economy involves more than having a
functional and engaging website, Wang stressed. "It involves
developing and creating value for business through developing
strategic networks and partnerships previously thought
unimaginable."
</P>
<P>
Participants believed that the Internet is one of the greatest
opportunities and one of the greatest threats to established
business. As a result, it is vital to establish a strong, quality
presence and it is no longer a "wait and see" approach, because
another site will start filling the needs of your customers with
the click of a mouse, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Asian Firms Urged to Take Lead in Digital Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
They also believed that Asian businesses are lagging in
developing their approaches to the Internet and early movers have
the chance to capture a disproportionate share of the future
profits. However, the Internet opportunity is so large and complex
for most businesses that it should be on the CEO's list of top
priorities, they said.
</P>
<P>
Todd Bradley, executive vice-president of the U.S. Gateway for
global operations, expressed his great concern over the issue of
the so-called "digital divide" opening up between the technology
haves and have-nots and called for information technology
companies throughout the world to shoulder special responsibility
to bridge the digital gap through humanizing the digital
revolution.
</P>
<P>
Intel Corporation's President and Chief Executive Officer Craig
Barrett also delivered an hour-long speech to elaborate on the
race for Internet leadership in Asia, and his speech brought the
discussion to a climax.
</P>
<P>
"The race is on for Internet leadership in Asia and the country
which embraces the Internet fastest will hold the leadership
position in the region," Barrett said, adding that he was
optimistic that Hong Kong will become the Internet hub of Asia
Pacific
</P>
<P>
Barrett predicted that China will overtake Japan to become the
second largest personal computer consumer nation with its
accession to the World Trade Organization, and he also expressed
his wish for expanding Intel's cooperation with Chinese companies
in the Internet sector.
</P>
<P>
According to Barrett, successful companies in the future will
be the ones which become 100 percent e-business by integrating all
aspects of their business from internal customers, external
customers and suppliers, partners and affiliates in an e-business
environment.
</P>
<P>
Participants also argued that e-business in the United States
may be a good applicable bellwether for what may happen in Asia
and what Asian businesses should learn from the U.S. curve.
However, they said, it also makes sense that e-business in Asia
may develop within a uniquely Asian framework. 
</P>
</TEXT>
