<HEADLINE> Prices Take Battering on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The slump came in line with the trend in many other Asian
markets which were broadly badly hit by the technology-led sell-
off on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) suffered a loss of 33.
84 points to end at 1,871.94 points in light trading and at one
point the fall in the broad market put Singapore stocks at a 13
month low of 1,828.79 points.
</P>
<P>
The total volume increased to 321.68 million shares valued at
619.18 million Singapore dollars (356.57 million U.S. dollars).
There were just 42 advances compared to 314 losers by the close of
the session.
</P>
<P>
The larger block was the 37.75 million parcel of Trek which was
transacted at 0.365 Singapore dollars per share. Ipco was the
second most heavily-traded stock which had 17.54 million units
done. NatElec was the next with 17.24 million counters changing
hands.
</P>
<P>
SIA led gainers of the day rising by 60 cents to close at 16.80
Singapore dollars. SIA 200 climbed by 50 cents to finish at 16.70
Singapore dollars. SembLog moved up 20 cents to end at 10.40
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Venture topped the decliners of the day plunging by 120 cents
to close at 14.80 Singapore dollars. Creative 50 and PacCent sank
70 cents each to finish at 43.30 and 12.00 Singapore dollars,
respectively. NatElec incurred a loss of 59 cents to end at 4.76
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the technology-led sell-off on Wall Street
overnight weighed heavily on the market sentiment and dragged down
the share prices.
</P>
<P>
They noted that banking stocks accounted for nearly half of the
index decline and electronics stocks also fell after the news of a
pause in the record-breaking pace of orders for computer chip
equipment sparked a sell-off in the U.S. technology sector.
</P>
