<HEADLINE> Guinea-Bissau's President, Military Leader Meet to Ease Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- President of Guinea-Bissau Kumba
Iala has met with the country's military leader Ansumane Mane in a
bid to seek ways for easing the tension between the civil and the
military authorities, a report reaching here said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held on Tuesday when Luis Amado, representative
of the Portuguese and the European Union (EU) aid institutions,
was paying his visit to Guinea-Bissau.
</P>
<P>
Amado called for an end to the tension and making preparations
for development plans to ensure continued foreign support for the
West African nation.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that this is the second meeting in five days
between the civil and the military leaders. No more details were
revealed.
</P>
<P>
Tension in Guinea-Bissau is mainly due to the civil
authorities' recent dismissal of the navy commander Lamine Sanha
without prior consultation with the military leadership.
</P>
<P>
Sanha was accused of freeing a Korean ship caught fishing
illegally in the Guinea-Bissau waters.
</P>
<P>
Iala said that he followed the government's recommendation and
has promised to maintain open channels of communication with the
military leaders.
</P>
<P>
Mane led the victorious Military Junta rebels who toppled the
then President Nino Vieira in May 1999. The post-conflict
transition period ended last February, when Iala, along with a new
government and parliament, took office following general
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
