<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Europeans to Send More Police to Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FLORENCE, Italy, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Wednesday urged its European allies to send more police to Kosovo
as a proof of their fair share in the mission.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the NATO foreign ministers, U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright said, "I ask that you do all you can to
meet your pledges there to help fill any remaining gaps that may
exist."
</P>
<P>
The presence of an international police task force in Kosovo
under the U.N. requirement is still below half of its proposed
strength, which is supposed to have 6,000 people in the Yugoslav
province to restore order and enforce law.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the Europeans need to prove their fair share in
Kosovo as the U.S. Congress has recently threatened withdrawing U.
S. troops from Kosovo in July next year if the Europeans make no
more contributions to the mission.
</P>
<P>
The United States has deployed 3,700 troops in Kosovo, while
other NATO member states and non-NATO countries combined have
contributed more than 32,000 troops to the multinational
peacekeeping force KFOR.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 people held demonstrations outside the meeting
place of NATO foreign ministers to protest against NATO meetings
in their city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
