<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sun Yat-sen Exhibition in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 24 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition featuring relations
between the city of Shanghai and revolutionary forerunner Sun Yat-
sen (1866-1925) is now being held in the east China metropolis.
</P>
<P>
Titled "Dr. Sun Yat-sen and Shanghai," the exhibition at the
memorial hall in Sun's former residence displays 116 historical
photographs and 28 historical objects, most of which have never
before been shown to the public.
</P>
<P>
The historical objects and documents reflect detailed
information on Sun's life and revolutionary experiences in
Shanghai, where he spent most of his time after the revolution of
1911 -- the Chinese bourgeois democratic revolution led by Sun
which overthrew the Qing Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
Some of the objects on display include Sun's name card, seal
and envelopes, a walking stick, and a telescope used by Sun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Encyclopedia on Chinese Towns Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- China has published an encyclopedia
about its nearly 20,000 small towns, covering the population and
the major products and market demand of the towns, as well as
projects in need of funds.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Civil Affairs has compiled information on the
small towns in China's central and western regions for inclusion
in the book, in an effort to cater to the demands of the present
national campaign to develop the country's vast western region.
</P>
<P>
The book is published by the Xueyuan Publishing House, and
provides the latest accurate, complete, and authoritative
information.
</P>
<P>
Authorities note that the book offers a large numbers of
business opportunities in an authoritative reference book that
helps overseas and domestic entrepreneurs to expand into China's
rural market.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the output value of township enterprises
in China's eastern, central, and western regions reached 6.62
trillion, 3.44 trillion, and 780 billion yuan, respectively, in
1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
