<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Crumbled Proxy Lebanese Militiamen Surrender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Over 1,500 militiamen, or nearly two-
thirds, of the 2,400-member pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army (SLA)
have surrendered to Lebanese authorities or anti-Israel Muslim
guerrillas by Wednesday morning, security sources said.
</P>
<P>
Of the SLA men who have surrendered since early May, 325 are
Druze, 220 are Christian and 1,010 are Shiite Muslims, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, over 5,000 SLA members and their relatives have fled
into Israel following the SLA collapse and Israeli pullout from
south Lebanon in fear of reprisal from Lebanese guerrillas now
taking over the region.
</P>
<P>
The SLA, which had acted as Israel's proxy in patrolling the
Israeli-occupied buffer zone in south Lebanon for the past two
decades, collapsed in days, which forced Israel to accelerate its
withdrawal, six-weeks ahead of its self-imposed July 7 deadline.
</P>
<P>
By early Wednesday, the Israeli troops have already completed
their hasty pullout from south Lebanon, ending 22 years of
occupation in the region, where it set up a self-styled "security
zone" in 1985 with the aim to guarantee its northern security.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Prime Minister Salim al-Hoss said Wednesday morning he
hoped Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon would lead to calm on
the border with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
"History will record that on this day the will of the Lebanese
and the sacrifices of their resistance have defeated the strongest
military force in the region," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Hoss added Lebanon would continue to struggle for the release of
Lebanese prisoners still held in Israel and the disputed Shebaa
Farms which Israeli said it seized from Syria in 1967 but both
Lebanon and Syria said Beirut has the ownership.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to struggle to regain our other rights from
Israel," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hezbollah, the main Shiite Muslim guerrilla group
fighting to end Israeli occupation in south Lebanon, said their
guerrillas would continue fighting for the release of their
Israeli-held members and the return of Shebaa Farms.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God backed by Iran and Syria, has
virtually taken full control of south Lebanon after the hurried
Israeli evacuation.
</P>
<P>
The border area with Israel has been relatively quiet since
dawn. Jubilant civilians returned to their home villages they had
not been able to visit for nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
With Hezbollah insisting on continued fighting to win over the
Shebaa region and release of more Lebanese detainees in Israel, and
Israel threatening serious reprisal once attacked, no one knows
what is in store after the liberation of the occupied lands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Congratulates Lebanon on Israeli Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami on
Wednesday congratulated his Lebanese counterpart Emile Lahoud over
the Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon, saying it was a result
of the Lebanese struggles against Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with Lahoud, Khatami said "the
government and people of Lebanon and their heroic resistance was a
symbol of the honor and dignity of the Arab and Islamic nations."
</P>
<P>
However, he cautioned that the future developments after the
just-concluded Israeli withdrawal should be watched "carefully and
vigilantly," the official Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops completed their withdrawal from south Lebanon in
the small hours of Wednesday, ending a 22-year occupation in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Khatami expressed hope that establishment of stability would be
witnessed in Lebanon and the liberation of more occupied lands
would be observed in future.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Lahoud said the Israeli withdrawal was in fact a
victory for both Iran and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Iran nurtured and is the backer of the Shiite Muslim Hezbollah
guerrilla group, the most prominent Lebanese resistance force
fighting against Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
Iran supplies Hezbollah, or Party of God, with weapons
transported through Syria, which is the main power broker in
Lebanon where it deploys 35,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud said the Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon would be
registered as a national day of resistance in the history of
Lebanon and "be honored forever."
</P>
<P>
He also expressed hope that withdrawal would be launched from
other occupied territories as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Although the people in south Lebanon are happy with the
withdrawal, "we have the same concern as the Islamic Republic of
Iran has that Israel has withdrawn from our soil today and it will
embark on occupation of Lebanese territory again," Lahoud said.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese government and Hezbollah have said they would continue
to fight for the release of Lebanese prisoners still held in Israel
and the disputed Shebaa Farms which Israeli said it seized from
Syria in 1967 but both Lebanon and Syria said Beirut has the
ownership.
</P>
<P>
Israel has threatened harsh reprisal once attacked after its
withdrawal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
