<HEADLINE> Int'l Envoys Meet Fiji Coup Leader, PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Senior United Nations and
Commonwealth envoys Wednesday met Fiji's coup leader George
Speight for talks in the country's besieged parliament house.
</P>
<P>
U.N. envoy Sergio Vieira de Mello and Commonwealth Secretary
General Don McKinnon were also allowed to see Prime Minister
Mahendra Chaudhry, who has been held captive since last Friday.
</P>
<P>
As he left, McKinnon said Chaudhry "looked quite well," despite
reports that Fiji's first ethnic Indian prime minister had been
beaten by his captors.
</P>
<P>
"I felt that they were all in reasonably good spirits
considering the obvious pressure they are under," McKinnon said
and urged the coup leaders to back down.
</P>
<P>
"One really hopes these people are prepared to step back from
the brink, realizing that there has already been damage to the
international reputation of Fiji," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speight remained defiant on Wednesday, refusing to release his
hostages.
</P>
<P>
However, sources close to Speight said he is expected to make "
his most significant announcement to date" later Wednesday night,
prompting speculation he may accept a compromise.
</P>
<P>
The decision by the international envoys to visit Speight came
on a day of shuttle diplomacy, in which McKinnon and de Mello also
met Fiji's President Ratu Sir Kamisese Mara, crisis mediator and
former Prime Minister Sitiveni Rabuka, and the Great Council of
Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
The Great Council of Chiefs met for a second day on Wednesday
to try to resolve the crisis and decide on the political future of
Chaudhry's government.
</P>
<P>
The chiefs have called for Chaudhry's release and backed Mara,
who wants to solve the crisis without breaching Fiji's
constitution.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Australia and New Zealand have condemned
Speight and warned of tough diplomatic and economic sanctions
against Fiji if he succeeds in his push to topple Fiji's
democratically-elected government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
