<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Economy Grows by 11.7 Pct in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's economy recorded a
growth of 11.7 percent in the first quarter of this year, the
highest quarterly expansion since the regional crisis of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The growth is broad-based with all sectors in the economy
registering positive output growth, Bank Negara (State Bank)
Malaysia Governor Zeti Akhtar Aziz told a press conference here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During the quarter under review, the manufacturing sector grew
by 27.3 percent, services sector by 6.3 percent, agriculture by 2.
9 percent, and both the construction and the mining sectors which
contracted by 5.6 percent and 3.1 percent, respectively, in the
last quarter of 1999 turned around to grow by 1.2 percent and 0.8
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Zeti said the 11.7 percent gross domestic product (GDP) growth
raised the GDP to 49.9 billion ringgit (13.131 billion U.S.
dollars), only marginally lower than the 50.3 billion ringgit (13.
236 billion dollars) recorded in the fourth quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
She said that the aggregate domestic demand expanded further,
recording a stronger growth of 12.2 percent in the first quarter
of 2000.
</P>
<P>
The external sector continued to remain favorable with the
trade surplus for the 11th consecutive quarter standing at 16.2
billion ringgit (4.3 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Strong trade surplus and portfolio capital inflows raised the
international reserves of Bank Negara Malaysia by 11.6 billion
ringgit (3.052 billion dollars) in the first quarter to 128.9
billion ringgit (33.9 billion dollars) at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's external debt position improved in the first quarter
of this year with total external debt declining by 3.4 percent to
1,545.3 billion ringgit (40.9 billion dollars) at the end of March
2000, equivalent to about 52 percent of gross national product (
GNP).
</P>
<P>
The governor said the higher growth was achieved under an
environment of low inflation with the annual rate of inflation as
measured by the consumer price index being lower at 1.5 percent
against 2.1 percent in the fourth quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's economy which contracted by 7.5 percent in 1998
registered a 10.6 percent GDP growth in the fourth quarter of 1999
and recorded a 5.4 percent GDP growth for the whole of that year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
