<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, Laos Step up Border Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Thailand and
Laos have agreed to forge closer cooperation to prevent and handle
problems along the border, the official Thai News Agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai was quoted as saying that the
agreement was reached at the ninth meeting of the Thai-Lao General
Committee on Peace and Order along the Border, which was held here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came out with resolutions that the joint committee
will meet at least twice a year, and a joint inspection will be
conducted by authorities concerned along the border once a year,
and regular surveillance conducted by security officers will be
limited in the internal areas of the countries, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Cross-border actions by security officers of the two countries
were allowed only when they are needed to assist or rescue
troubling people along the Mekong River, based on the humanitarian
reason, according to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
If there is any urgent incident, an emergent meeting of the
Joint Committee would be called and a joint inspection would be
conducted immediately, said Chuan, who chaired the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He stated that the two countries also agreed to exchange useful
information, and to jointly prevent and decisively crack down
drugs trade and trafficking along the border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
