<HEADLINE> EPO Test "Almost Certain" for Sydney, IOC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 24 (Xinhua) -- International Olympic Committee (IOC)
top official Jacques Rogge believes doping controls to detect the
banned hormone erythropoietin (EPO) were "almost certain" to be
ready for the Sydney Olympics starting in September.
</P>
<P>
"At the beginning of the year, the IOC, because of past
disappointments, did not believe that such a test could be
completed before Sydney," he told the French sports daily l'Equipe.
</P>
<P>
"A month ago, it was fifty-fifty. Today, it is almost certain,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
An Australian laboratory and a French research center will soon
publish their results in scientific magazines. Publication is the
first stage for a doping test to be validated and accepted legally,
Rogge said.
</P>
<P>
Rogge said that the process of validation of the new EPO test
should be completed before the Olympics, which start on September
15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
