<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weizman Welcomes Troop Withdrawal From South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman
expressed welcome to the troop withdrawal from south Lebanon, which
was completed at predawn Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The completion of Israeli troop withdrawal from south Lebanon
was a very special movement because we have ended 22 years of
presence in south lebanon," said Weizman.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal will make the resumption of Israel's peace talks
with Syria and Lebanon more likely, he said during a meeting with
Shao Huaze, president of China's People's Daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli pullout was carried out without agreement with Syria
or Lebanon, Weizman said, adding that Israel would fight back if
any military actions are taken against Israel after the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
He urged Syria to take concrete actions for a resumption of
Israeli-Syrian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace talks came to a halt in January after
two rounds in the United States, due to Israel's refusal to promise
the full return of the Golan Heights it captured from Syria in the
1967 Middle East War.
</P>
<P>
Weizman said Israel will continue to push the Middle East peace
process ahead.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Israeli president said his country is trying to
find solutions to all issues in the final-status talks with
Palestinians, among the toughest of which are Jerusalem,
Palestinian refugees, Jewish settlements, border, security
arrangement and water.
</P>
<P>
On Israeli-Chinese relations, Weizman expressed the belief that
China will play a more active role in world affairs in the years to
come.
</P>
<P>
He hailed Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to Israel in
April as a "historic event" that strengthens the relations between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Shao and his party arrived here on Sunday for a five-day visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
