<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Sets Up Anti-Corruption Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid Wednesday installed an anti-corruption team to back the
government's program in eradicating rampant corruption in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The team consists of 25 members and is chaired by former chief
justice of the Supreme Court Adi Andojo Sutjipto.
</P>
<P>
The president said that the team must investigate anyone who is
suspected to be involved in corruption practices, and the members
of the team also must be free from any link to corruption.
</P>
<P>
The team was set up based on a decree issued by Attorney
General Marzuki Darusman on May 23. The decree states that the
attorney general is the coordinator of the team.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in regard to the case of former President Soeharto
who has been facing corruption charges, Wahid reiterated that the
government will pardon him for the sake of national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
"Forgiving former President Soeharto is one of the conditions
under which national reconciliation process can be carried out,"
Wahid said, adding that the forgiveness will be granted to the
former president only after the court declares him guilty in
corruption cases.
</P>
<P>
He urged Western countries to understand the idea of
forgiveness in Soeharto's case.
</P>
<P>
"We only need to get the good things from the West and maintain
(the good things) in our country," Wahid said, noting that Western
countries prefer to use confrontational ways rather than reach
reconciliation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
