<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC ENT Congress Begins in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The second SAARC ENT (ear, nose
and throat) Congress kicked off here Wednesday with the theme of "
extending ENT services to the community" of the countries in the
South Asian region.
</P>
<P>
At the four-day meeting, about 500 participants from the SAARC
(South Asia Association for Regional Cooperation ) countries and
some 100 doctors and specialists from other regions are discussing
at the four-day meeting the prevention and cure of ENT diseases in
the SAARC countries, especially in villages and communities where
such diseases are pervasive.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, we will acquire knowledge of current issues
affecting the diagnosis, evaluation and treatment of
otolaryngological and related disorders," said professor M.
Alauddin, president of the SAARC Association of Otolaryngologists,
at the inaugural ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Alauddin suggested the arrangement of short and long term
fellowship programs for the otolaryngologists in SAARC countries
to promote the training and exchange of information and expertise
among them.
</P>
<P>
Hearing impairment is a major disease leading to physical
disability in the SAARC countries, with India, Pakistan,
Bangladesh and Nepal being the worst-affected. SAARC also includes
Bhutan,the Maldives and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Due to economic constraint and lack of human resources
development, ENT services are not available to the peripheral
areas of the countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
The current congress is co-organized by the Society of
Otolaryngologists of Nepal and the SAARC Otolaryngologists
Association, which was formed at the first SAARC ENT congress held
at Dhaka, Bangladesh in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the association is to promote the
exchange of scientific views and transfer of technology regionally
and globally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
