<HEADLINE> Mindanao Problem Only Temporary, Says Estrada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
said Wednesday that the problems spawned by the conflict in
Mindanao are only temporary, and that he is doing his best to
exhaust all possible means to resolve them, the Philippine News
Agency (PNA) said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering in Guimaras province in the Visayas,
Estrada said the resolution of these problems will bring about
true peace and progress in Mindanao and the entire country.
</P>
<P>
"We have a minor problem in Mindanao, but this is temporary.
Once this is resolved, we can have true peace and progress,"
Estrada was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the PNA, the president arrived at Guimaras
Wednesday morning from Bacolod city with some members of his
cabinet to inaugurate some projects. He will be back in Bacolod
City prior to his trip to Metro Manila in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Estrada asked the people to help resolve these
problems by rallying behind his administration.
</P>
<P>
The president also asked insurgent groups to lay down their
arms and help him instead in transforming the nation into a land
of total peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
"We must resolve these problems. We cannot progress as a nation
if we don't unite. All I ask is a little sacrifice so we can
overcome these problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the past weeks, the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF)
and Abu Sayyaf extremists in some parts of Mindanao have
challenged government authority by attacking state-owned
installations and civilian-populated areas, and taking hostage
innocent civilians and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, after engaging government troops in weeks of fighting,
has agreed to resume peace talks with the government in Cotabato
City on May 30.
</P>
<P>
Government troops, meanwhile, continue to work for the safe
release of the remaining two teachers and five schoolchildren who
were among the 31 civilians taken hostage in Basilan in March.
</P>
<P>
Negotiators are also preparing to secure the freedom of 21
tourists abducted from Malaysia last month and later taken to Jolo
island by Abu Sayyaf extremists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
