<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Revenue Collection Short of Goal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Revenue Authority
collected 40.4 billion shillings (538.6 million U.S. dollars) in
the first quarter of the current financial year, about two billion
shillings short of the target, newspapers here reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner General John Msafari attributed the shortfall to
the unfavorable economic conditions as the overall growth in Gross
Domestic Product stood at 1.3 percent, significantly lower than
the same period of the previous two years.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the performance of some tax heads such as the
Road Maintenance Levy Funds and air passenger service charges
recorded a phenomenal growth.
</P>
<P>
The road levy increased by 23 percent to 1.98 billion shillings
(26.5 million dollars) in the quarter from 1.61 billion shillings
(22.3 million dollars) over the same period last year, Msafari
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the air passenger service charges rose by 240
percent to 500 million shillings (6.67 million dollars) in the
first three months from 230 million shillings (3.06 million
dollars) over the same period in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
