<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Rent Generators to Avert Power Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government will spend
9.1 billion shillings (121 million U.S. dollars) in the next four
months to avert a looming power shortage in the country.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Energy Minister Francis Masakhalia said Tuesday the
government would rent an emergency diesel power plant at a cost of
30 million dollars per month, including generators and fuel,
newspapers here reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Generator leasing is one of the few options to solve the power
shortages as a result of a fall in national production after a
long dry spell.
</P>
<P>
A two-year continuous drought, the harshest in 40 years, has
led to an electricity shortfall of between 154 and 360 megawatt in
the off-peak and peak hours respectively.
</P>
<P>
Masakhalia said a 12-hour power rationing schedule is to be
introduced across the country starting Monday, with industrial and
commercial consumers having power between 6:30 am and 6:30 pm
everyday except Sundays. 
</P>
</TEXT>
