<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Rebels Release Russian Pilots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Angolan rebels have turned over the
five Russian aviators held captive last year to the Zambian
authorities, informed source said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the rebel National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) said the five Russians, pilots of
two planes shot down in northeast Angola respectively on May 12
and June 30 last year, were handed over to the authorities in the
Zambian village of Hangana on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The release, long sought by Moscow, was "a gesture of pure
humanism in response to appeals by the aviators families and
prestigious personalities and statesmen," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The source declining to be identified said that UNITA thanked
the Zambian government for its guarantee to take the released
captives to Russia in safety.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan rebels also warned in the statement that all
nations with citizens in Angola "under any pretext" did not have
"minimum guarantees of security" in the country's war zones, which
it claimed embraced all the Angolan territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
