<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall Further in Tokyo, Nikkei Hits New Closing Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices fell further in Tokyo
Wednesday, with the benchmark Nikkei hitting a new closing low for
the year after dipping below 16,000 several times for the first
time in almost a year.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange plunged 274.29 points, or 1.68
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 16,044.44 for the sixth
straight trading day of decline.
</P>
<P>
The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all First
Section issues, dropped 14.91 points, or 0.98 percent, to 1,504.93,
also a closing low for this year.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to 662.31 million shares
from Tuesday's 614.59 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's decline on Wall Street, particularly that of the
technology-heavy NASDAQ composite index, weighed on Japanese
information and high-tech issues Wednesday, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Mining, textile and wholesale issues also faced strong selling.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, brokerages were the biggest winners, rising 3.84
percent as a group, following their recent decline.
</P>
<P>
Gainers also included electric power and gas firms, nonlife
insurers and consumer finance companies.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 830 to 439, while 119 issues closed unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
