<HEADLINE> Deaf Child Receives US$100,000 in Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Zou Weiyi, a seven-year-old boy who
became deaf due to medical negligence, has received over 830,000
yuan (some 100,000 US dollars) in compensation in northeast China'
s Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The Liaoning Provincial Higher People's Court announced a final
judgment requiring the Dandong Railway Hospital, the defendant in
the case, to pay 838,764 yuan to the child, who suffered from an
overdose of gentamycin when he was five months old.
</P>
<P>
Zou's family brought charges against the hospital in June 1998,
asking for 1.2 million yuan in compensation. The judgment made by
the Intermediate People's Court of Dandong City said that the
hospital must pay 460,000 yuan to the boy.
</P>
<P>
Both the family and defendant appealed to the Provincial Higher
People's Court.
</P>
<P>
As there are no laws on physical injuries caused by medical
malpractice in China, the judges reviewed numerous files and
consulted experts in Beijing before making their final judgment.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that such a law is a must, so that Chinese
judges can deal with the increasing number of disputes between
doctors and patients.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dunhuang in NW China to Build New Tourism Economic Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The city of Dunhuang, renowned for
the Buddhist art of the Mogao Grottos in northwest China's Gansu
Province, has decided to build a new tourism economic zone by
taking advantage of the country's current drive to develop its
western region.
</P>
<P>
The new zone will be located at Yitang Lake, 20 km east of
downtown Dunhuang and 15 km from the Mogao grottos, which was
added to the World Heritage List in 1987.
</P>
<P>
The zone will cover an area of 5 square km, and the first phase
of construction will cost 800 million yuan (96 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The city government has stipulated preferential policies to
attract domestic and overseas investment for the zone.
</P>
<P>
Some 530,000 Chinese and foreign tourists visited Dunhuang last
year, and the city's income from tourism was 166 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The city is making an effort to open new scenic spots and
attract visitors in numbers approaching one million by the year
2010.
</P>
<P>
Dunhuang was once an important town along the ancient Silk Road
linking Central Asia with China. It has rich tourism resources and
historical sites, including the Mogao Grottos, Mingsha Hill, and
the Yueya (Crescent) Spring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
