<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast Grain Base Focuses on Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China, a major grain
production base in China, is shifting from quantity to quality in
order to make grain production more profitable.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning Province plans to establish a quality seed base with
400,000 yuan (48,200 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to a sample survey, maize with rich oil, lysine, and
starch will be widely planted in the province. The acreage for soy
beans and potatoes will increase by 666,700 hectares, to account
for one fifth of cultivated land in the province.
</P>
<P>
Jilin and Heilongjiang provinces will practice crop rotation in
planting soy beans and maize.
</P>
<P>
Northeast China yields the best soy beans in the country.
However, the output of soy beans does not exceed various kinds of
grains. Consequently, China had to import more than three million
tons of soy beans each year.
</P>
<P>
Jilin will subsidize soy bean planters with 138 million yuan (
16.6 million U.S. dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign businesspeople are welcomed to join agricultural
reforms in Liaoning Province. The provincial government hopes to
invite foreign partners to invest in the processing of farm
products, crop planting, environmental protection, and the
agriculture high-tech sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Ibises Born in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, May 24 (Xinhua) -- A baby crested ibis was recently born
at the Shaanxi Ibis Protection Center on the Qinling Ranges in
northwest China, and it is the 52nd ibis born there this year.
</P>
<P>
According to officials from the center, this year saw a record
number of newly-born ibises. Twenty-eight were born naturally
while 24 were bred artificially.
</P>
<P>
They attributed the higher birth rate to better environment and
effective protection measures taken by the center which monitors
them 24 hours every day.
</P>
<P>
In general, reproduction and survival rates of ibises in
captivity are declining, they noted, adding that setting them free
is the ultimate goal.
</P>
<P>
Ibises are endangered species distinguished by its red crest,
gray plumage and hooked beak. Population has grown from merely
seven in 1981, when it was first found in northwest China, to 200
as a result of environmental protection measures adopted by the
local government. The measures include a ban on fertilizer
application and lumbering in areas close to the species natural
habitat.
</P>
<P>
The origin of the endangered species has been traced back to
over 60 million years ago, with large flocks formerly existing in
most of China, Japan and Germany. But now the species is found
only in China, mostly in mountainous areas in the Qinling Ranges
in northwest China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railway for Energy Project Opens to Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The major section of the
Shuozhou-Huanghua Railway has just opened to traffic as part of an
ambitious energy project which is expected to channel energy
products -- mainly coal -- from western areas to east regions in
China.
</P>
<P>
The completed section extends from Shenchi county in northern
Shanxi Province to Suning county in northern Hebei Province. It is
420 kilometers long and has been finished four and a half months
ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
The Shuozhou-Huanghua Railway, linking Shenchi county with
Huanghua port in Hebei Province is about 588 kilometers long, and
is expected to cost 17.4 billion yuan. The railway will be the
second largest railway line for coal transportation from west to
east China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
