<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Ancient Tomb Unearthed in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, May 24 (Xinhua) -- A tomb of a noble woman dating back
some 800 years ago was discovered in north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The tomb was excavated in the Erlian Basin. Archaeologists said
discoveries of its kind have been rare in Inner Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
The woman was wearing a bronze belt and bracelets and a barrel-
shaped hat made of birchbark which can be found in historical
textual documents.
</P>
<P>
A bronze belt with 15 plates was also discovered. The belt is
the first of its kind ever found by archaeologists. According to
Mongolian history, Mongolian women worshipped the white deer and
male ancestors worshipped the wolf as totems.
</P>
<P>
The tomb will greatly help research on ancient Mongolian
history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
