<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading Turkish newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet (Freedom):
</P>
<P>
-- Devlet Bahceli, deputy prime minister of Turkey and leader of
Nationalist Action Party, accused on Tuesday that Russia was
adopting "expansionist" policies in the Caucasus and the Central
Asia.
</P>
<P>
He made the allegation amid Russian President Vladimir Putin's
recent visit to Turkmenistan, during which the two countries signed
an agreement on Russia's purchase of 50 billion cubic meters of
Turkmen natural gas for the coming 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- It was reported that Duran Kalkan, a member of the
Chairmanship Council of the outlawed separatist Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK) in Turkey, said he would desert the organization
following a contact with the Turkish security units.
</P>
<P>
He asked the Turkish security units not to disturb him in
turn. "It is no longer possible for the PKK to get results from
either political or military actions. I decided to leave it and
live in a foreign country from now on in secrecy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Daily News:
</P>
<P>
-- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) will start monitoring
Turkish banking sector following a meeting in September.
</P>
<P>
The IMF, which demands absolute transparency in the data of
financial system, will send its banking experts every three months
to Turkey to monitor the developments in the sector and inspect the
financial reports of each bank.
</P>
<P>
Turkey will receive 4 billion U.S. dollars in loans from the IMF
under an agreement between the two sides, so it must implement
reforms pushed for by the global financial organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
