<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Closes All Border Crossings after Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
METULLA, Israel, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Shortly after completing its
troop withdrawal from south Lebanon early Wednesday, Israel closed
all crossings along the Israeli-Lebanese border, announcing that
there is no single Israeli left in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Fatma Gate, the main border access the Israeli troops and
its Lebanese allies South Lebanon Army (SLA) used in the
withdrawal, was also closed to traffic.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of Lebanese working in Israel's sea port city of Haifa
gathered at the crossing, waiting for Israel's permission to return
to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy that south Lebanon is now in our hands after the
Israeli withdrawal and we don't want to continue our work in
Israel, we want to return home," a young man told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"But we don't know how long we will wait here, because Israel
has closed this crossing we used to pass," he added.
</P>
<P>
Not far from the gate is a large Israeli military base named
Good Fence. Inside the base, several military tents were set up to
temporarily house the returned Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
"We are very happy to return home from south Lebanon," a young
solider said, "but our officers told us not to talk to reporters
about the withdrawal."
</P>
<P>
An Israeli army bus driver, asked not to be named, said he was
told to wait for further orders. "I don't know, maybe we have to
move to other places along the border to protect Israel's northern
security," he said.
</P>
<P>
Only military trucks can be seen inside Metullah, a scenic city
in northern Israel, and all the city residents have moved to the
south in fear of cross-border rocket attacks from guerrillas now
taking over south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
As ordered by Prime Minister Ehud Barak, the Israeli military
completed troops withdrawal predawn Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
