<HEADLINE> Starvation Looming In Cyclone-Hit Areas In Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Starvation is looming in the Cyclone
Eline- ravaged districts in Zimbabwe as food reserves have sunk to
dangerously low levels, the daily Herald reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview here Tuesday, Red Cross Society Secretary
General Bongayi Mundeta said her organization which is actively
involved in mobilizing relief goods for flood victims is left with
only two months' food supply.
</P>
<P>
Other main actor, the Civil Protection Department, is also
running out of food.
</P>
<P>
More than 300,000 people were left homeless and without food
when Cyclone Eline-induced floods hit the country in February this
year.
</P>
<P>
Mundeta said while the situation was still manageable, it was
evident that food supplies will soon run out as the number of
people in need of relief aid continues to rise.
</P>
<P>
Director of the Civil Protection Department Madzudzo Pawadyira
also confirmed that food supplies will soon come to an end.
</P>
<P>
Mundeta also expressed concern over the number of children
suffering from malnutrition, which has shot up to 10,000 over the
last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
"Signs and symptoms of malnutrition are very evident in the
majority of children in the affected areas. We have started a
food supplementary program in Manicaland province and plans are
afoot to extend it to other areas hit by the floods," she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
