<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Farmers to Lose 110 Million U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Farm occupations by war veterans and
landless blacks in Zimbabwe have inflicted an estimated 110
million U.S. dollar damages of crops and livestock on white
commercial farmers, the Commercial Farmers' Union of Zimbabwe has
said.
</P>
<P>
Livestock losses have been estimated to be 65 million U.S.
dollars while crop losses stand at 50 million U.S. dollars, the
daily Herald quoted Vice- President of the union Collin Cloete as
saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Cloete said the forecast of the wheat crop was down by 30
percent from last year's 325,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
He said if the farm occupations continue, there would be a
further decrease in the commodity.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of soya bean farms had been occupied by war
veterans. The quality of the crop had been affected by delays in
harvesting and additional exposure to rain.
</P>
<P>
Cloete said farm occupations had also affected cotton
production as there is now a shortage of casual cotton pickers.
</P>
<P>
There is an estimated five percent or 40,000 tons loss of grain
due to increased theft, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The late announcement of this year's maize producer price,
coupled with the uncertainty in the industry relating to maize
marketing and the current environment of farm invasions, could
result in a reduction of 15 percent in the 2000/2001 production
season," he said.
</P>
<P>
Other major losses have been forecast in horticulture, coffee,
the dairy sector, beef and poultry sectors.
</P>
<P>
War veterans have occupied about 1,000 white farms since
February to press for an equitable redistribution of land.
Negotiations are going on between the government, farmers and war
veterans to resolve the matter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
