<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Foreign Ministers Meet in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FLORENCE, Italy, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from 19
member countries of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
met here Wednesday to discuss a whole range of issues including
the U.S. national missile defense system (NMD), Russia as well as
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General George Robertson said at the opening
session of the two-day meeting that these issues are key to
guarding the security of the Euro-Atlantic region and making the
military alliance ready to face the challenges of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright brought to
Florence an American initiative of trading weapons within NATO so
as to help patrol the exports of high-technology weaponry to non-
NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that the American initiative was also aimed at
promoting the interoperability, a NATO jargon for weaponry
standardization. The 78-day NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia
last year exposed problems in weaponry standardization among its
member states.
</P>
<P>
The European allies, however, expressed their worries about the
NMD which may only cover North America. They warned that the
project could provoke another round of arms race.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov is joining the meeting
later Wednesday. It will be the first time that the Russian
foreign affairs chief meets with NATO counterparts after the
western military alliance slighted Russian opposition to air
strikes against Yugoslavia last year.
</P>
<P>
NATO is trying to amend its relations with Russia and was
persuading the Russians to allow it to open, as planned, a liaison
office in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers are expected to take stock of their
Kosovo peacekeeping mission as NATO-led multinational troops have
been stationed in the Yugoslav province for almost a year by now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
