<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus Rises 10.3 Percent in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Japan's merchandise trade surplus
rose 10.3 percent in April from a year earlier to 1,143.9 billion
yen (10.7 billion U.S. dollars) as an upsurge in exports
outperformed an increase in imports, the Finance Ministry said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The double-digit growth, which follows a 14.9 percent decline
in the surplus in March, is attributed to increasing shipments to
Asia and the United States, the ministry said in a preliminary
report.
</P>
<P>
Overall exports in April totaled 4,376.6 billion yen (40.9
billion dollars), up 8.8 percent, while imports came to 3,232.8
billion yen (30.2 billion dollars), up 8.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Exports grew as shipments of semiconductors and other
electronic parts, autos and optical equipment for scientific use
gained 21.6 percent, 7.7 percent, and 17.4 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Imports were also up, helped by a 68.5 percent jump in crude
oil purchases, a 46.9 percent rise in liquefied natural gas
imports and a 16.3 percent gain in office equipment procurement.
</P>
<P>
Japan's politically sensitive trade surplus with the U.S.
climbed 26.2 percent to 725.3 billion yen (6.8 billion dollars),
marking the third consecutive month of growth.
</P>
<P>
With other Asian countries, Japan's trade surplus jumped 55.4
percent to 443.9 billion yen (4.1 billion dollars) on the back of
a recovering trend in the region's economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japan's trade surplus with the 15-member European
Union (EU) decreased 2.6 percent to 347.1 billion yen (3.2 billion
dollars), posting the first decline in three months.
</P>
<P>
Japan's merchandise trade balance is measured on the basis of
goods clearing customs and is reported before adjustments for
seasonal variations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
