<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA to Step up Anti-doping Checks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 24 (Xinhua) -- A top world soccer official on
Wednesday announced plans to step up anti-doping tests.
</P>
<P>
Michel D'Hooghe, president of FIFA's medical commission, said
the world body and UEFA's medical commission had decided to
conduct out-of-competition testing for the first time during the
run-up to the Euro 2000 finals, which start on June 10.
</P>
<P>
"We have the conviction that some athletes take some products,
namely anabolic steroids, during the preparation period," he said
in a keynote address at the Second Asian Congress on Science and
Football.
</P>
<P>
"If doping tests are done only during the games, the
metabolites of these products have disappeared from the urine," he
said.
</P>
<P>
D'Hooghe said random tests would be conducted on four of the 16
teams in the tournament. In the 2002 World Cup six to eight teams
would be tested.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference later that doping in soccer was now
"relatively under control. Let's keep it that way. But we should
continue to be vigilant by conducting random checks."
</P>
<P>
The FIFA medical chief said in the last six months only two to
three cases were reported worldwide but the world body views the
battle seriously.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at the congress, organized by the Asian Football
Confederation, D'Hooghe said FIFA gave great attention to fighting
doping because the effects on athletes in general can be
catastrophical.
</P>
<P>
"Amphetamines caused the deaths of many young athletes.
Combination of many products such as cocaine and anabolic hormones
led to irreversible psychotic reactions," he said
</P>
<P>
He also highlighted the use of performance-enhancing drugs such
as EPO, somatotropic hormones and perfluorocarbons.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that we will never win the fight against doping
-- new products will continue to enter the scene and we will
always be behind the detection.
</P>
<P>
"There is an important parallel market (the doping industry)
providing young athletes with forbidden and dangerous products," D
'Hooghe said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
