<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Tension in Bangladeshi Enclave in India Worsens  By Chen Jian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The tension in a Bangladeshi enclave
inside Indian territory has worsened following a fresh report that
India's Border Security Force (BSF) personnel abducted 11
Bangladeshis from the enclave early Tuesday Morning.
</P>
<P>
The 11 Bangladeshi citizens were abducted from the Mashaldanga
enclave under the district of Kurigram, about 400 kilometers
northwest of Dhaka, while Bangladesh Rifles (BDR) and BSF held a
Company Commander-level flag meeting to settle the Mashaldanga
enclave incident which took place last Thursday, The Independent
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred Indians, allegedly supported by BSF personnel,
intruded into the Bangladeshi enclave of Mashaldanga, and abducted
Bangladesh nationals, set ablaze 55 houses and looted valuables
and cattle.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi nationals were, however, released later, while
more than 10 women and children reportedly received injuries
during the attack lasting at least one hour.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the enclave is reported to be in acute shortage of
food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies for its more than 2,
000 inhabitants, who are now virtually confined in the Indian
territory since last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government is closely watching the situation in
Mashaldanga enclave. When asked if the government has any plan to
lodge official protest with the Indian government, Syed Moudud Ali,
a director general of the Foreign office, said they are waiting
for latest development over there.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Secretary General of main opposition
Bangladesh Nationalist Party Abdul Mannan Bhuiyan on Tuesday
expressed grave concern over the continued attack by Indian
terrorists backed by Indian border guards in Mashaldanga enclave.
He demanded the government to take immediate steps to stop such
attacks from across the border.
</P>
<P>
During the company commander-level flag meeting Tuesday, the
BDR and the BSF agreed to conduct a joint inquiry into the
Mashaldanga enclave incident which took place on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, "BSF took responsibilities" for
the incident and assured their BDR counterpart of taking pragmatic
steps to stem recurrence of such incidents in the future. They
also agreed to ensure security to more than 2,000 people of the
517-acre enclave.
</P>
<P>
However, when asked about the abduction of the 11 persons from
the enclave, the BSF did not admit the allegation, saying those
people might be picked up by Central Reserve Police of India.
</P>
<P>
Since the company commander-level meeting was not productive as
expected, sources said a battalion commander-level meeting between
the two border forces is likely to take place within a couple of
days, at which all enclave issues will be discussed and the
proposed high-level joint inquiry committee will be formed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
