<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Welcomes India's Offer to Evacuate Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"If the situation arises and India can help, we will welcome it,
but I don't know if the ground situation is such that we need to
evacuate the troops immediately," Sri Lankan Deputy Foreign
Minister Lakshman Kiriella was quoted as saying in the port city
of Chennai in south India on Wednesday morning before leaving for
Colombo. Kiriella was said to have been in Chennai and Bangalore
on a "private visit" since May 20.
</P>
<P>
India decided on Tuesday that it would help evacuate Sri Lankan
armymen trapped in Jaffna peninsula provided the Sri Lankan
government raised a formal request under some "proper conditions."
</P>
<P>
The next four or five days would be very crucial, as it would
then be known whether the situation requires measures like
evacuation, Kiriella told the press in Chennai. "It all depends on
the ground situation," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He also promised that the Sri Lankan government would "do
anything to create a peaceful environment in Jaffna" for the
safety of any Indian evacuation mission, the PTI reported.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on New Delhi's overall approach to the present
situation in Sri Lanka, the minister said his country understood
India's limitations, given the fact that there is a coalition
regime now, whereas in 1987, when India intervened in the ethnic
crisis in Sri Lanka, the Congress government under Rajiv Gandhi
was "all powerful."
</P>
<P>
He said that prospects for peace are better now as, unlike in
1987 when India alone was involved, several other countries like
Norway and the United States are now eager to resolve the problem.
</P>
<P>
"The world has changed a lot. The prospects are much better for
peace now," he was quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
