<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Political Unrest Affects Philippine Economy (Part 1)  By Chen Zhanjie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Since the beginning of 2000, the
escalating fighting between government troops and Moro rebels, the
long-running hostage saga, and the bombings incidents across the
country are affecting the Philippines' economy.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, the political unrest has turned the local stock market
to the worst-performing one in Asia marked by the continued free-
fall.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the 33-share main index in the Philippine Stock
Exchange plunged to a new 19-month low at 1,421.09 due to broad-
based selloff. On Tuesday, the index lost a further 7.42 points to
1,404.67, which is nearly off 35 percent from the close of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Accompanying the stock market, the Philippine peso breached the
support level of 42 pesos against the U.S. dollar on Tuesday, also
hitting a 19-month low.
</P>
<P>
The local currency ended at 42.37 pesos against the U.S. dollar
at the Philippine Dealing System, shedding an additional 45.5
centavos from Monday's 41.915 pesos.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the heightened political risk arising out of the
intensified Moro insurgency in Mindanao and the dragging-on of a
foreign-hostage crisis in Jolo island would further depress
markets already hurt by prospects of slower economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The bombing of two shopping malls in Metro Manila, including
the largest one in the country, sparked concern that the military
conflict in Mindanao may be spilling over into the national
capital region, they said.
</P>
<P>
The bomb attacks followed a flare up in fighting between
government troops and Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) members
in Mindanao which has left 113 government soldiers dead and nearly
500 wounded so far.
</P>
<P>
Although the two sides have principally agreed to resume peace
talks on May 30, the conflict in Mindanao is far from over. The 15,
000-strong MILF has been fighting for an independent Islamic state
in the south for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has warned that negotiations with the
1,000-man Abu Sayyaf which is holding 21 hostages in Jolo island
could last for "months." The hostages, including 10 western
tourists, were seized from a Malaysian resort on April 23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
