<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Further U.S. Rate Hike to Threaten Thai Recovery: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Arporn Chewakrengkai, economic adviser to Thai Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai, was quoted by Wednesday's the Nation newspaper as
saying that a half-point hike would be acceptable for the country,
which still has enough liquidity of capital in the economic system.
</P>
<P>
However, she said, if the United States tightens the screws on
interest rates more than expected, say by one percent, it could
start creating problems for Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Arporn explained that a wider rate gap between the U.S. and
Thailand will result in more foreign capital flowing out of the
latter as investors sought higher gains for parking money in the
former.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the U.S. decided to nudge up its short-term interest
by half percentage point, and signaled that more increase is
likely after the five rate hikes in the past 10 months had done
little to slow down the over-heated U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
Thai financial markets as well as the neighboring markets saw a
heavy sell-off driven by offshore investors after the U.S. rate
hike last week. The Thai stock market plunged to a 15-month low,
and the baht broke through its psychological level of 39 against
the US dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
