<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Slaps West for Barring It From Dayton Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia Tuesday strongly
condemned the U.S.-led West for blocking it from attending the
Dayton meeting, which is being held in Brussels on Tuesday and
Wednesday to review the Dayton peace accord's implementation.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav government said the West's act to bar Yugoslavia's
participation in the gathering of foreign ministers from the
countries that signed the 1995 peace accord has violated the
Dayton treaty and undermined peace and stability in the region,
the Yugoslav state news agency Tanjug reported.
</P>
<P>
By doing so, the West has also grossly violated U.N. Security
Council Resolutions 1022 and 1031, under which Yugoslavia, one of
the parties that signed the peace agreement, has the equal right
to see to it that the agreement is implemented, the government
said.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnia peace agreement, reached in Dayton, Ohio, the
United States, in November 1995 by leaders of Bosnia, Serbia and
Croatia, under the mediation of Russia and major Western countries
including the United States, Britain, Germany and France, put an
end to the three-and-a-half-year war in the former Yugoslav
republic of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Russia, a traditional ally of Yugoslavia, has boycotted the
Brussels meeting by not sending representatives.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia warned the United States and its European followers
that they must take full responsibility for all the consequences
resulting from the violations of the Dayton peace agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
