<HEADLINE> Sydney Airport to Handle Pre-Games Rush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Government
Wednesday said the Sydney International Airport was well equipped
to handle an expected rush leading into the September 15-October 1
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Air traffic control had altered landing schedules to allow the
airport to process an average of 4,000 passengers per hour, which
was inside its full capacity.
</P>
<P>
Federal Immigration Minister Philip Ruddock said: "We'll be
ready to handle it even if there are variations to the slot times
that have been identified."
</P>
<P>
Ruddock noted that the first of an estimated 50,000 electronic
visas for athletes, officials and the media had been issued, which
would also reduce queuing times for customs and immigration
processing.
</P>
<P>
He said the peak time for arrivals was expected to be two to
three days before the Opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The New South Wales state government Monday opened a new
Airport rail line, linking the airport in eastern Sydney with the
city center. 
</P>
