<HEADLINE> Fiji Chiefs Begin 2nd Day of Meeting on Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
While the chiefs were meeting at the Queen Elizabeth II army
barracks on a hill 6 km outside Suva, the capital itself was
becoming increasingly tense.
</P>
<P>
A chicken factory was burnt down overnight, there were reports
of outlying villages being pillaged and torched, and the general
mood was tense after the chiefs Tuesday threw their support behind
Ratu Mara and not the coup leaders.
</P>
<P>
Foreign journalists Wednesday morning began leaving the
parliamentary compound in central Suva where coup leader George
Speight is holding Fiji's Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry and
several ministers hostage.
</P>
<P>
Reporters left about 8 a.m. Fiji time Wednesday after becoming
concerned for their safety when Speight angrily accused the
international media of portraying him as a terrorist.
</P>
<P>
Speight rejected Tuesday's decision by the nation's Great
Council of Chiefs to support Ratu Mara.
</P>
<P>
As members of the Great Council of Chiefs met, United Nations
and Commonwealth representatives arrived to try to help resolve
the Pacific Island nation's crisis.
</P>
<P>
The UN's East Timor representative, Sergio Vieira de Mello,
arrived along with Commonwealth Secretary-General Don McKinnon and
both went into talks with Mara.
</P>
<P>
Vieira de Mello said he hoped there would be a role for the U.N.
to play in a peaceful resolution of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"That is why the secretary general sent me here," he said,
adding it was too early to say if he would meet Speight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
