<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spanish, French Leaders Stress Anti-Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Spanish and French leaders held a
summit meeting Tuesday in Santander, a city in northern Spain, to
exchange views on cracking down on terrorist activities,
structural reform of the European Union (EU), and bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Attending the summit were Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria
Aznar, French President Jacques Chirac, Primer Minister Lionel
Jospin, and 13 ministers from the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Both Spain and France are satisfied with what they have
achieved in bilateral cooperation, especially in cracking down on
terrorist activities. They also admitted however that more
efforts should be made to improve work in this regard, and
coordinate with local police and judicial departments in a bid to
weaken and eventually smash the terrorist organization ETA.
</P>
<P>
President Chirac said at the meeting that more measures should
be adopted to reform the structure of the EU when France takes
over its office. Both sides agreed that a decision should be made
without delay on the expansion of the EU, supporting the euro
dollar, and developing the local economy.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, they also exchanged views on improving the
prospects of economic situations in Europe and Latin America,
cooperation between Europe and Mediterranean countries, the
situation in the Middle East, as well as transportation and
economic cooperation between Spain and France.
</P>
<P>
The first summit meeting between Spain and France occurred in
Madrid in 1987. Since then, a meeting has been held annually in
both countries in turn. Spain and France maintain good economic
relations and trade. France is Spain's largest trade partner. In
1999, trade between the two countries amounted to 7,000 billion
Pesetas (about 38.88 billion U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
