<HEADLINE> U.S. Launches Joint Anti-Narcotic Program With Guatemala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Southern Command Chief
General Charles Wilhelm Tuesday launched a 'war' against drug
trafficking in the Central American country of Guatemala, a
dispatch from the capital said.
</P>
<P>
United States and Guatemala will step up their cooperation in
battling drug trafficking under the program "Maya-Jaguar." The
program will allow American soldiers to take part in anti-narcotic
operations being carried out in Guatemala, Wilhelm was quoted as
saying at the headquarters of Guatemala's anti-narcotic police.
</P>
<P>
Under the "Maya-Jaguar" plan, 40 U.S. marines will work with
580 staff members of Direction of Anti-narcotic Operations (Doan)
of Guatemala. They will operate three Blackhawk and two Chinook
helicopter gunships, some land vehicles, and a boat to patrol
Guatemala's Caribbean coast.
</P>
<P>
Guatemala's Congress passed a bill on April 13 that allows 99 U.
S. soldiers to work in cooperative programs to help fight drug
trafficking in this Central American country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
