<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Tories File Suit over Party Name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 23 (Xinhua) -- The Progressive Conservative Party
of Canada filed suit Tuesday against the newly formed Canadian
Reform Conservative Alliance for using the word "Conservative."
</P>
<P>
The federal Tories, who hold 20 seats in parliament, accused
the Alliance of violating the Trademarks Act by stealing their
party name.
</P>
<P>
"The basis of the lawsuit is that the PC party has continuously
used the word Conservative since the formation of the party before
confederation" and "the name is something that we have to actively
protect," said a Conservative party statement.
</P>
<P>
The Tories brought the case to the Federal Court before the
leadership vote next month by the alliance, which was formed in
March by the former official opposition Reform Party and
provincial Conservatives mainly from Alberta and Ontario.
</P>
<P>
The creation of the alliance was reported to cause an exodus
from the federal Tories, who prefer to remain independent and
believe the defection is rooted in a "calculated and deliberate
attempt" by the alliance to give the false impression the two
parties have formed a political alliance.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Canada's chief electoral officer, Jean-Pierre
Kingsley, rejected a Tory objection by ruling that the name of the
alliance "does not so resemble" other party names in the country.
</P>
<P>
But the Tories vowed to fight on for the exclusive use of the
party label "Conservative." The newly filed suit could take six
months to two years, according to the Conservative party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UEFA to Operate Licensing System for European Clubs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 23 (Xinhua) -- European soccer clubs will soon have
to gain a UEFA license if they want to compete in UEFA's club
competitions, its executive committee agreed on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The licenses will be issued only if a club satisfies four
criteria regarding infrastructure and administration, and
financial, legal and sporting matters.
</P>
<P>
A working party chaired by UEFA vice president Senes Erzik of
Turkey has been looking into licensing clubs, and the new system
could start in 2002.
</P>
<P>
One of the innovations is that a club will not gain a license
unless it operates a youth development system which UEFA hopes in
time to see encompass youngsters from the age of 12.
</P>
<P>
Countries like Spain and Germany already operate a licensing
system for their senior clubs.
</P>
<P>
Studer said it would be up to UEFA's 51 national associations
to monitor the system on behalf of the ruling body. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
