<HEADLINE> Zhivanevskaia Fails to Set World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Nina Zhivanevskaia missed to regain
her women's 50 meters backstroke world record at the Mare Nostrum
swimming meeting in Barcelona on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian-born Spaniard won her event easily in 28.88 seconds.
Japan's Mai Nakamura set the record of 28.67 on April 23,
eclipsing two-hundredths of a second off the mark Zhivanevskaia
had swam two weeks before.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian Agnes Kovacs, who had set a European record of 31.34
for the women's 50 meters breaststroke in the first Mare Nostrum
meeting on Sunday in Monaco, won the event in 31.82.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's world champion Sarah Phoewe pushed Kovacs all
the way but finished second in 31.85.
</P>
<P>
Multiple world, Olympic and European champion Alexander Popov
of Russia pulled out of the meet at the last minute. 
</P>
