<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UEFA to Ask FIFA to Ban Young Players from International Transfer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Young soccer players under the age of
18 will be banned from moving abroad if a decision taken by UEFA's
executive committee on Tuesday is accepted by FIFA, world soccer's
governing body.
</P>
<P>
The committee agreed to ask FIFA, which has ultimate control
over transfers, to impose an international ban to stop young
players being exploited or put at risk.
</P>
<P>
Markus Studer, UEFA's deputy chief executive, said too many
players aged as young as 14 or 15 were moving abroad and there was
absolutely no guarantees about their safety, especially if the
move was not successful.
</P>
<P>
UEFA is also concerned about the number of young players from
around the world who are being transferred into Europe at a very
young age with little chance of them making the success.
</P>
<P>
UEFA is powerless to stop the international transfers of
players, even between its own 51 member nations while FIFA is the
legally empowered football authority to deal with this matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
