<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sheffield Wednesday Close in on Kinnear  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Sheffield Wednesday are focusing on
"one individual" in their search for a new manager, with Joe
Kinnear believed to be their prime target.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday need an experienced man at the helm for a rebuilding
job at Hillsborough following the club's relegation to Division
One.
</P>
<P>
And the 53-year-old former Wimbledon manager has the right
credentials for the job.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday chairman Howard Culley told the Sheffield Star: "We
still have a number of candidates. We are looking down the road
with one particular individual but there is no firm deal with
anyone. We are not there. Until a deal is done we are not going to
make any announcement."
</P>
<P>
Peter Shreeves took over as Wednesday's caretaker manager after
the sacking of Danny Wilson in March following the 1-0 Premiership
defeat at Watford.
</P>
<P>
Kinnear took over as Wimbledon boss in 1992 and took the club
to the semi-finals of the FA Cup and the Coca-Cola Cup in 1997.
</P>
<P>
He had to stand down in June of last year after suffering a
mild heart attack before the Dons' match against Wednesday at
Hillsborough in March 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
