<HEADLINE> More Doublts over Charleroi Match Safety  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 23 (Xinhua) -- More concerns have been raised over
the venue for England's match with Germany at Euro 2000.
</P>
<P>
The two teams meet at Charleroi on 17 June but a Belgian MP
believes the 30,000 capacity stadium is not safe, according to the
BBC on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tony Van Parys, a Christian Democrat (CVP) member of the
parliamentary home affairs committee, said the stands were
unusually steep and questioned evacuation procedures because the
stadium is in a built-up, residential area.
</P>
<P>
His comments followed an inspection of the stadium with
security and town officials.
</P>
<P>
"The difference is not great but one had always told us the
norm (for sloping stands) had been respected. I would not like to
find myself on the stands if there was a crush," he said.
</P>
<P>
There have been concerns from many corners of the footballing
world, particularly considering the potential for trouble between
English and German fans.
</P>
<P>
Two other Euro 2000 matches are due to be played at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
England coach Kevin Keegan gave his full backing to the stadium
after a visit in April and Euro 2000 officials say security
measures are adequate. 
