<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Border Residents Calmly Accept Army Pullout From Lebanon By Lou Jian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIRYAT SHEMONA, Israel, May 24 (Xinhua) -- After the last
Israeli soldier withdrew from south Lebanon early Wednesday
morning, residents in Israel's northern border town of Kiryat
Shemona calmly accepted the pullout.
</P>
<P>
The populous town along the border between Israel and Lebanon
had been a major target of Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas' Katyusha
rocket attacks in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and set up a security zone in
south Lebanon in 1985 with a self-claimed aim of protecting its
northern settlements from cross-border guerrilla attacks. Since
then, Hezbollah, backed by Iran and Syria, has been spearheading a
war of attrition to oust the Israeli occupation forces and launched
rocket attacks on northern Israel off and on.
</P>
<P>
The Shemona residents traditionally adopted a negative attitude
toward Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's plan to pull Israeli
troops out of Lebanon by July because the move will endanger their
normal lives and harm their economic interests. In April and In
early May, these residents also announced a strike against the
withdrawal which was approved by Israeli cabinet in March.
</P>
<P>
However, most residents interviewed by Xinhua on Wednesday
termed the withdrawal as a positive step and supported Barak's
policy toward Lebanon, including his remarks that if Israel is
attacked after its troop withdrawal from south Lebanon, the Israeli
military will launch reprisals not to be limited to the border
area.
</P>
<P>
The pullout was accelerated in the past 48 hours after the pro-
Israeli South Lebanon Army (SLA) in the so-called security zone
collapsed suddenly under the pressure of Hezbollah. More and more
SLA militiamen surrendered to Hezbollah guerrillas who sped up
their move to take over strongholds gradually abandoned by Israelis
recently.
</P>
<P>
Zievi Edna, a shopkeeper, said she suffered great economic loss
because she had to close her shop in recent days in fear of the
chaos in the town. However, she believed Israel should pull its
troops out of south Lebanon as the territory is not Israel's soil.
</P>
<P>
A senior resident named Mike said he congratulated Israel
Defense Forces officers on the successful withdrawal as it caused
no Israeli casualties during the move, adding that Israelis should
no more shed their blood in other countries' territories. He said
he agrees to Barak's opinion on the Lebanon issue.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he thought the withdrawal posed threats to his life,
Yakov Schwartz, a young worker, said it was the same security
expectation before and after the withdrawal and the former security
zone no longer helps protect the lives in Kiryat Shemona.
</P>
<P>
Sarah Naor, a bank staff, agreed with Schwartz, but she stressed
that if Israelis were again under Hezbollah's Katyusha rockets'
attack after the pullout, the Israeli government should surely
take "strong steps" to retaliate.
</P>
<P>
Mike, held the same view on the issue, but added the strikes
against Lebanese should only be limited to infrastructure sites,
such as power stations, bridges, and should not cause any civilian
casualties.
</P>
<P>
A volunteer working for Magen David, or Israel's Red Cross
organization, said Barak could do better than what he did today,
but he believed the withdrawal is still good. The man, who rejected
to reveal his name, was among the volunteering doctors and nurses
sent from Israeli port city of Haifa to reinforce the northern
border areas.
</P>
<P>
Timna Orland, a 15-year-old student, said she and her family
members totally support the withdrawal and if a general election is
held three years later when she can vote, she will surely choose
Barak as prime minister because of his brave move regarding
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Before Wednesday's sundown, the center of Kiryat Shemona
returned to normal life again and most people moved out of the bomb
shelters where they had spent two nights.
</P>
<P>
Doddi Orlivy, a young computer specialist, said he believed
peace is the most important thing in the world, and expressed the
hope that Israelis and Lebanese will not point guns at each other
again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Withdrawal from S. Lebanon Conducive to Advancing Peace Process by Qi Deliang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 24 (Xinhua) -- As ordered by Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak, Israel early Wednesday conducted an
unexpectedly hasty troop withdrawal from south Lebanon, ending its
22 years of military occupation of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Under the cover of darkness, some 1,000 Israeli soldiers
streamed out of the security zone into Israel in tanks and armoured
personnel carriers. The withdrawal, six weeks ahead of Barak's
self-imposed July 7 deadline, did engender the sense of a chaotic
retreat which some Israelis did not want to see.
</P>
<P>
The rapid collapse of the Israeli-allied South Lebanon Army(SLA)
in south Lebanon during the past few days was the main reason which
forced Barak into heeding to the requests of the Israeli military
and ordered the pullout ahead of schedule. Opposition parties and
several local commentators dismissed the pullout as a humiliation.
</P>
<P>
Despite all this, the withdrawal has also in fact brought about
some structural changes in the regional politics and diplomacy. And
in the long run, the pullout and its impact will be conducive to
moving the Middle East peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
For Barak, the core of the Middle East issue is Israel's
reconciliation with the neighboring states and all Arab nations as
a whole, through peaceful negotiations. The materialization of this
goal mostly depends on Israel's return of its occupied territories,
such as the West Bank, the Golan Heights and the security zone in
south Lebanon, to the Palestinians, the Syrians and the Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops invaded and occupied south Lebanon in 1978 with a
self-declared aim of halting cross-border attacks by Palestinian
guerrillas. After its invasion of Lebanon in 1982, Israel set up
the 850-square-kilometer security zone in southern Lebanon in 1985
for protecting its northern security.
</P>
<P>
Till now, at least 900 Israeli soldiers have been killed in
south Lebanon, while tens of thousands of Lebanese lost their lives
in fighting the war of attrition, which the Israelis know they can
not win.
</P>
<P>
Barak's decision to end this tragedy was mostly viewed as the
right one, and the withdrawal could help pave the way for an
earlier realization of reconciliation between the Israelis and the
Lebanese in the days to come.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal is closely related to Israel's difficult peace
talks with Syria, the major power broker in Lebanon. Israeli
leaders have long contended that Syria has been trying to pressure
Israel into peace concessions by supporting Lebanese guerrilla
group Hezbollah, or Party of God, to launch attacks on Israeli
outposts in the security zone.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, Israel has also tried to use the withdrawal as a
pressure card to force Syria back to the negotiating table and
soften its positions concerning the return to Syria of the Golan
Heights which Israel captured during the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which deploys about 30,000 troops in Lebanon
as peacekeepers, have insisted on the integration of their talks
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Now both Israel and Syria are facing a serious dilemma. Both
sides lost their important pressure cards after Israel's
withdrawal, which could force the two sides to think about how they
could resume the peace talks in the days to come.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace talks, which resumed last December in
Washington after a nearly four-year-long hiatus, have been
suspended since January after two rounds of talks. A summit meeting
between U.S. President Bill Clinton and his Syrian counterpart
Hafez al-Assad in March failed to bring the two sides back to the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians welcomed the withdrawal, terming it as a great
Arab national victory and a victory for the Palestinians as well.
</P>
<P>
Barak stated that the withdrawal was carried out under the U.N.
Security Council Resolution 425, approved in 1978. The Palestinians
said that it has set a good example which will help Israel solve
its territorial problems with the Palestinians. Moreover, the
withdrawal can make more room for Israel to concentrate on
finishing its final-status talks with Palestinians on time. The two
sides have set a September 13 deadline for reaching a final peace.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal was a big event in the Middle East peace process.
But the situation along the Israeli-Lebanese border is not stable
and nobody knows what could happen there in the near future.
</P>
<P>
However, questions remained as to whether Israel can avoid
renewed entanglement in Lebanon. Barak explicitly warned both
Lebanon and Syria that Israel would retaliate harshly if Israel is
attacked after the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has not sent more peacekeeping forces right now into
south Lebanon. So, Barak still has a lot of homework to do after
the withdrawal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Hail Israeli Pullout from Lebanon as Victory of Lebanese People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary-General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid on Wednesday hailed Israel's just-completed withdrawal
from south Lebanon as a great victory of the Lebanese resistance.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released for the event, Abdel-Meguid praised
Lebanese people's wisdom and strength in ousting the Israeli
occupation troops from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League chief called on the United Nations Security
Council to follow up and verify Israel's withdrawal from Lebanese
territories in accordance with the U.N. Security Council
resolutions 425 and 426.
</P>
<P>
Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and carved up a border strip in
south Lebanon as a so-called "security zone" in 1985 to allegedly
protect its northern border area from cross-border attacks by
Lebanese Muslim guerrillas. The U.N. Security Council adopted the
two resolutions after Israeli invasion, demanding immediate and
unconditional Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli government had decided in March to pull out from Lebanon
by July 7. However, it completed the troop withdrawal from southern
Lebanon at early hours on Wednesday, ending its 22-year occupation
of the area.
</P>
<P>
"If the Israelis are really seeking a comprehensive and just
peace (with the Arabs), they should abide by the U.N. resolutions
related to their pullback from the (Syrian) Golan Heights and the
Palestinian occupied lands, including Jerusalem, and give up
intransigence and procrastination on all tracks," Abdel-Meguid
said.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured the Golan Heights from Syria in the 1967 Mideast
war. The two countries have yet to resume peace talks on the return
of the strategic plateau. The Palestinians and Israel have been
negotiating for a final peace agreement on the status of the
occupied territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
