<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Thirds of Romanian Exports Go to EU Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 24 (Xinhua) - Romania's exports amounted to 2399.
2 million U.S. dollars and imports reached 2642.6 million,
increasing by 27 percent and 14.5 percent, respectively, for the
first quarter of the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Exports to developed countries increased by 22.5 percent and
exports to European Union's countries increased by 21,1 percent.
The weight of these countries in the total of Romanian exports was
70.9 percent for the developed countries and 64.8 percent for the
European Union's countries for the first quarter of the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Exports to developing countries, which have a weight of 15
percent of the total of exports, increased by 24.9 percent.
Exports to countries which go through a period of transition
registered a 58.7 percent-increase.
</P>
<P>
Industrial products represented 96.9 percent of the total of
exports for the first months of the year 2000, while the
agricultural and forestry products had a weight of 3.1 percent
only.
</P>
<P>
Romania's main exports partner countries for the first three
months of the year 2000 are Italy, Germany and France.
</P>
<P>
As far as imports are concerned, developed countries held a
weight of 63.1 percent that increased by 6.9 percent as against
the same span of time in 1999. Imports from the European Union's
countries were 56.5 percent of the total of imports. They
increased by 7.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Romania's main imports partner countries are Italy, Germany,
and the Russian Federation.
</P>
<P>
According to the information supplied by the National
Statistics Commission, the trade deficit was 243.4 million U.S.
dollars for the first three months of the year. As far as the
relation with the European Union is concerned, the balance of
trade was in excess for the first three months, the surplus being
59.9 million U.S. dollars The highest trade deficit registered in
the relation with countries which go through a period of
transition in Central and Eastern Europe: minus 256.1 million
dollars. 
