<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Airways Plunges Into Red </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 24 (Xinhua) -- British Airways (BA) has made an
underlying loss of 244 million pounds in the latest financial
years, its worst showing since it was privatized.
</P>
<P>
Lord Marshall, BA's chairman, blamed the"disappointing" results
on over-capacity on its long-haul routes, cut-price European
competition, fuel prices and the strong pounds.
</P>
<P>
He said expansion by Lufthansa, Air France and American
carriers had led to "a double-figure rise in capacity which was
nowhere near matched by demand levels", causing widespread
discounting.
</P>
<P>
Rod Eddington, the new chief executive who took over from the
ousted Bob Ayling in May, said he expected recovery on the North
Atlantic. "I think we're moving towards a much more rational
balance of supply and demand."
</P>
<P>
Analysts are watching to see whether the new chief executive
will be able to implement the cost-cutting and down-sizing
strategy laid out by his predecessor, who was sacked in March
after a troubled four-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
However, Eddington declined to spell out BA's cost-cutting
plans or how many jobs would go, but he said he did not believe
there would be any compulsory redundancies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
