<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Program for Romania Creates 30,000 New Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 24 (Xinhua) -- A major part of the World Bank's
projects portfolio in Romania addresses social and human
development issues. Two of these projects have been completed and
six are under implementation and making satisfactory progress,
according to the World Bank Office in Romania.
</P>
<P>
The Employment and Social Protection Project offered financing
for 700 micro-projects which drew in about 56,000 laid off workers
while 30,000 new jobs have been created. This project also made a
significant contribution to the passing of the law on the new
public pensions system and the drafting of the private pensions
law.
</P>
<P>
The Social Development Fund Project has so far offered 120
grants to poor communities for small scale infrastructure works or
social protection.
</P>
<P>
Under the Education Reform Project over 160 new textbooks were
printed, new curricula and assessment and examination measures
have been developed; the program also financed the creation of
teacher training centers equipped with computers.
</P>
<P>
The Higher Education and Research Reform Project offered over
650 grants for education and research programs. Under the School
Rehabilitation Program, the first three fully rehabilitated
schools were re-opened last month; other 700 schools will be
rehabilitated by the end of this project.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian and the World Bank experts are currently focusing
on the methods meant to improve the quality of education in rural
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
