<HEADLINE> U.S. Calls on Lebanon Government to Take Charge of Security Near Border with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Wednesday that all parties concerned should be cooperative on the
withdrawal of Israeli troops from the southern Lebanon and Lebanon
's government take charge of security near the border with Israel.
</P>
<P>
"it's important that everyone cooperate on this," State
Department spokesman Philip Reeker said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
He said Israel's pullout had to be "confirmed" by an emissary
of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan. And he said a U.N.
peacekeeping force "will assist the government of Lebanon in
assuring its effective control over the area."
</P>
<P>
Reeker said the United States had made it clear that "all
foreign forces should withdraw from Lebanon and that Lebanon
should exercise full sovereignty over all of its territory."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman again called for restraint as Hezbollah
guerrillas rushed in to fill a void as a result of Israel's
withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Annan plans to increase the U.N. peacekeeping
force, but the United States has not offered to contribute any
troops.
</P>
<P>
Reeker said Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who is in
Florence, Italy, attending a meeting of NATO foreign ministers,
had telephone conversations with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and conferred with French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine, over
the Israeli pullout.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary and others have called for restraint and calm,"
Reeker said. "In this regard, the Lebanese government has a
responsibility for security in the south. And it's important that
they move quickly to assume that responsibility." 
</P>
</TEXT>
