<HEADLINE> Canada's Western Premiers Meet on Regional Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Canada's annual Western Premiers
Conference officially opened Wednesday in Brandon, Manitoba, with
leaders expected to coordinate their policies for the regional
development.
</P>
<P>
Premiers of British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan, Manitoba,
as well as Yukon and Northwest Territories converged in Manitoba's
southern town Tuesday night to compare notes on issues ranging
from medicare to highway development.
</P>
<P>
Alberta's Bill 11 on the provincial health policy, which was
passed earlier this month, is one of the hot topics during the two-
day meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ralph Klein, the Alberta Premier, told his counterparts upon
his arrival Tuesday that Alberta's legislation is quite consistent
with the legislation that was passed by British Columbia,
Saskatchewan and Manitoba.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to fears expressed by some of his counterparts
that Alberta's Bill 11 will allow operation of privately funded
health clinics, which they believe to be a step toward a two-tier
health-care system, away from the current federal system.
</P>
<P>
Yukon and Northwest Territories are more concerned with their
regional economic development and highway building. Their leaders
urge for more federal support for things "like improving the
national highways system."
</P>
<P>
Canada's western premiers are scheduled to end their
discussions Thursday and travel to the International Peace Gardens
to meet with the governors of Idaho, North Dakota and South Dakota
of the United States on cross-border disputes in trade and
agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
