<HEADLINE> Guatemala, US Hold Joint Anti-drug Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Guatemalan agents and U.S. military
men participated on Wednesday in the destruction of a poppy
plantation in the San Marcos Guatemalan province, bordering Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The operation was the first of its kind within the anti-drugs
plan between Guatemala and the United States, named Maya-Jaguar
2000, which started on Tuesday, according to reports coming from
the Guatemalan capital and received here.
</P>
<P>
U.S. helicopters located the plantation and Guatemalan agents
destroyed its 2,500 poppy plants in a faraway village in San
Marcos, west of Guatemala, said the Civilian National Police of
Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
The Maya-Jaguar anti-narcotics operations will continue in
Guatemalan territory during the next two weeks, it said.
</P>
<P>
The poppy plants destroyed had a black market value of 200,000
US dollars, according to the source.
</P>
<P>
In the Maya-Jaguar operation participated 40 U.S. marines, tens
of technicians and specialists and four armed helicopters and a
ship, while Guatemala participated with 580 agents, over 100
vehicles and four fast boats.  
</P>
