<HEADLINE> 200 Nigerians Feared Dead in Riots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 200 people have been
reportedly killed and hundreds of building have been burned down
in the renewed riots in Nigeria's northern city of Kaduna, said a
source reaching here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Reinforced military soldiers and police have been sent into
Kaduna, capital of Kaduna State in northern Nigeria, after two
successive days of clashes between Muslims and Christians in the
city, said the source.
</P>
<P>
The latest clashes broke out on Monday after residents of a
mainly Christian neighborhood blamed Muslims for the killing of a
local man, and the fighting was reported to have quickly spread to
the outlying districts of the city on Tuesday night, according to
local police.
</P>
<P>
The authorities are concerned about the risk of violence
spreading to other parts of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, a night-time curfew has been imposed by the police
authorities after the breakout of the clashes, and the police also
issued a warning that anybody found with illegal firearms would
not only face prosecution but would be treated as an armed robber.
</P>
<P>
The renewed clashes came just three months after riots between
Muslims and Christians in the city, in which more than 1,000
people reportedly died, over the proposed implementation of
Islamic law Sharia. 
</P>
