<HEADLINE> Uganda, Rwanda to Withdraw Troops From Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and Rwanda are expected to
withdraw their troops on Thursday from Kisangani, a northeastern
city in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), in line with a
demilitarization order signed by military chiefs of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
A timetable has been worked out for the full implementation of
the order, signed on May 21 and coming into effect on Thursday,
said a Ugandan government statement issued on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement, signed by Amama Mbabazi, Uganda's State Minister
for Foreign Affairs, said the withdrawal and redeployment of the
forces include those of the rebel forces in Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Observer Mission in the Congo would deploy
its force to exercise neutral control over the demilitarized zone
around the city and airports of Kisangani, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
During the process of demilitarization of Kisangani and
thereafter, no party shall use force or threaten to use force
against any other party or parties, said Mbabazi in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Rwandan troops went into clashes on May 5 and May 8
in Kisangani where they had their armies stationed to back rival
rebel factions fighting against the DRC President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The clashes between the Uganda People's Defence Forces and the
Rwanda Patriotic Army in Kisangani were most regrettable and
should never have happened, said Mbabazi.
</P>
<P>
Mbabazi also assured that Uganda' s relations with the
government and the people of Rwanda remains firm and that the
Ugandan government will not jeopardize the relationship that has
long existed between the peoples of the two neighboring countries.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
