<TEXT>
<P>
GUATEMALA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- About 1,000 indigenous women
representatives of 14 of the 22 Guatemalan provinces demanded on
Wednesday during a pacific march for an end to discrimination and
a respect to their rights.
</P>
<P>
Anastasia Pacheco, Secretary of Women Affairs in the Peasant
and Indigenous National Coordination, termed their situation as "
difficult" because, she said, there is no respect neither for
their customs nor for their cultural identity.
</P>
<P>
Maya women and peasants demanded on Wednesday the respect for
their right to organize and for an end to discrimination.
</P>
<P>
They also urged for a reduction in basic food products price,
agricultural inputs, land, decent housing, literacy programs and
the creation of employment sources with fair salaries and
treatment.
</P>
<P>
Besides, they asked for school support for widows who lost
their husbands during the last armed conflict, and the creation of
the required mechanisms to carry out the Agreement on Identity and
Rights of Indigenous Peoples signed between the Government and the
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Indigenous women complained for having being left marginalized
in the summons to the "Governing Pact" prepared by the Guatemalan
President despite having been the main victims during the 36-year-
long civil war (1960-1996).
</P>
<P>
The leader said that many women live in extreme poverty and
misery, and that in communities in the interior of the country
they are threatened for demanding their rights.  
</P>
</TEXT>
