<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moldova Asks EBRD to Re-assess Funding Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 24 (Xinhua) - Republic of Moldova asked the
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) to re-
assess conditions to resume the funding of Moldova, saying the
present conditions "are not the most advantageous" .
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by Moldovan Deputy Premier Andrei Cucu,
also the economics and reforms minister, on his return Tuesday
night from an EBRD board of governors meeting in Riga, the
Moldovan news agency Bass-Press reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Cucu said the Moldovan delegation met in Riga with EBRD senior
officials who "practically accepted" Chisinau's proposals.
</P>
<P>
So far, the interest rate on EBRD short- and medium-terms
credits was under 5-6 percent. After the inclusion of Moldova in
the category of poor developing countries in 1997, the foreign
lenders -in particular the World Bank - hacked the interest rate
for loans offered to Chisinau down to 0.75 percent. The World Bank
grants 35-year credits under International Development Agency
conditions.
</P>
<P>
A total of 17 projects worth 145 million euros are being
carried out in Moldova with EBRD support.
</P>
<P>
But Cucu expressed regret that "the projects launched in 1995-
1996 have not been complete yet," said Cucu, adding that there are
"many problems" related to the construction of the Giurgiulesti
oil terminal.
</P>
<P>
The deputy premier said that the Moldovan authorities asked the
EBRD to re-assess a number of projects due to the severe social
and political situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
An EBRD mission is expected in Chisinau after June 5 to discuss
with Moldovan officials every project separately. 
</P>
</TEXT>
