<HEADLINE> APEC Telecommunications Meeting Opens in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANCUN, MEXICO, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The Fourth Ministerial
Meeting on Telecommunications and Information Industry of the Asia-
Pacific Economic Council (APEC) opened on Wednesday in Mexicao's
Tourist Center of Cancun.
</P>
<P>
 Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, who presided over the
opening ceremony of the regional meeting, said that many of the
most dynamic world economies belong to APEC, which drives
transformations in their communities and economies.
</P>
<P>
Regarding its cooperation with APEC, he said that Mexico always
supports national and international efforts to promote the
development of telecommunications, which increases productivity
and competitiveness of many other sectors in the country and in
the world.
</P>
<P>
He said that telecommunications have a high economic and social
value, which constitutes the most important incentive for its
continuos technological innovation.
</P>
<P>
Amb Serbini Ali, General Director of APEC, underscored the
importance of the celebration of the international forum.
</P>
<P>
The three-day regional meeting has two parts: the participation
of senior government officials and the participation of ministers,
and it will close on May 26, four days after its opening on the 22.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen ministers and vice ministers from member countries to
the regional organization participate in the event along with
senior government officials, scholars and businessmen.
</P>
<P>
They will mainly analyze the challenges and opportunities for
the telecommunications and information industry, above all,
originated from the convergence between their services and
technologies.
</P>
<P>
They will deal with the issue of closing the gap between
developed and developing counties, in regards to access to
telecommunications and information.
</P>
<P>
Also, the participants will discuss on the issue of developing
initiatives of projects and programs to develop trade and
investments in the region, basically in the promotion of
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
After three days of discussions, it is expected that some of the
documents drafted will be signed as the Declaration of Cancun.
</P>
</TEXT>
