<HEADLINE> Mexico to Charge Hard Penalties Against Internet Criminals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Mexican Vice Minister of
Communications Jorge Silberstein proposed on Wednesday to adopt
more severe penalties against those who miss-use the Internet, for
instance propagating "cyber-viruses".
</P>
<P>
Silberstein told the press that it is necessary to take
comprehensive steps by the 21 economies of the Asia-Pacific
Economic Council (APEC).
</P>
<P>
The senior official will participate in the 4th Ministerial
Meeting of Telecommunications and Information Industry, which will
take place from Wednesday to Friday at the Mexican tourist resort
of Cancun, in the state of Quintana Roo, 1,223 kilometers east of
Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
"Hackers" using ever complex and hard to detect systems, must
be severely punished in order to fight them off, he said.
</P>
<P>
The "Love Virus" recently propagated from Filipines via
Internet destroyed world information valued in more than 10
billion US dollars, said the official, who expressed his
satisfaction for the capture of the creators of the virus.
</P>
<P>
Through Internet, many diverse crimes, like fraud, have been
perpetrated, said the official.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, known as Telmin-4, is part of APEC, whose members
are: Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, China, South Korea, USA,
Philippines, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, New
Zealand, Papua-New Guinea, Peru, Russia, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The central issue of the meeting will be the convergence in
technologies and services, as well as the review on actions
related to telecommunications.
</P>
</TEXT>
