<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Army Chief Quits in Defense Cut Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, May 24 (Xinhua) -- General Hans-Peter von Kirchbach,
the general inspector and highest officer of German armed forces
Bundeswehr, announced to resign, the Defense Ministry Wednesday
said in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
It was the general's own decision to quit after 15 months in
office, stressed Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping, declining to
give further explanation.
</P>
<P>
"General von Kirchbah was not sacked,- it was his own decision
to quit," he said.
</P>
<P>
General Harald Kujat has been chosen to replace General von
Kirchbah as chief of staff after July 1, said Scharping.
</P>
<P>
The resignation of General von Kirchbach "is the end of a long
discussion process," said Scharping, referring to the recent
disputes around the "structural reform" for leaner and more
professional German armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Scharping indicated that Germany should
sharply cut the soldiers and defense budget, change its cold-war
era compulsory forces into a professional and flexible one.
</P>
<P>
"The Bundeswehr (German forces) must become more mobile,
flexible" to cope the regional conflicts together with its western
partners, Scharping said.
</P>
<P>
But General von Kirchbach, who became a national hero after
organizing German army to resist a huge flood in year 1997 as a
tank corps commander, was known for his resistance to sharp cuts
in soldier numbers.
</P>
<P>
Scharping's plan has won the back of Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder, said Charima Reinhardt, a government spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder called Scharping's plan "on the right way to
successfully solve the hardest mission" of his coalition cabinet,
according to the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
And an independent defense panel recommended the cabinet
cutting the number of soldiers to 240,000 from the present 370,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
