<DOCNO> XIE20000524.0371 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gates Calls Business Leaders to Prepare for Third Wave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft chairman Bill Gates
said Wednesday that the Internet is rapidly entering a new third
phase, beyond mere connectivity and simple transactions, and
shifts into online services delivered over different devices.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking in Seattle at Microsoft's fourth annual CEO
Summit which attracts more than 160 business leaders from around
the world. The event was largely closed to the media, but Gates'
speech was released right after the meeting's opening. He did not
mention Microsoft's antitrust battle with the U.S. Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
Gates described the Internet evolution from a one-way portal
and content-driven entity, where businesses sought an Internet
presence, to a service-oriented, two-way tool for businesses.
</P>
<P>
In the third phase of the Internet, he said, businesses will
utilize tools that enhance relationships, provide interactive
services and expand communication to increase knowledge-sharing
beyond application.
</P>
<P>
"We are transitioning from an off-line economy into an online,
digital economy," Gates said. He shared his belief that the
successful companies in this next generation of the Internet will
be those that renew their customer commitment, strengthen ties
with partners and use the power of leading-edge Internet services
to enable seamless interaction both within their organization and
throughout their business model.
</P>
<P>
Among his predictions, he said mobile devices will go far
beyond their existing functions, e-mail addresses will be unified,
and business supply chains that have been paper-oriented will be
Internet-oriented.
</P>
<P>
"Wireless technologies are really going to change how we think
about the Internet," Gates said. "The fact that you have high-
speed data connectivity will really change things a lot."
</P>
<P>
He said PC itself will not slow down in any way. "It changes
every year dramatically. Every year the PC keeps getting better.
It always leads the way."
</P>
<P>
Instant messaging, voice-over video, and video conferencing
will make communication on the desktop a richer experience, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
