<HEADLINE> U.N. Says Agreement May be Near on Khmer Rouge Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The agreement to try
Cambodia's Khmer Rouge may be near and the United Nations is going
to send its chief legal counsel to the country to wrap up the
details, U.N.spokesman Fred Eckhard said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Eckhard said no date had been set for
the visit by the chief legal counsel, Hans Corell and it would
take place when a mutually convenient time can be agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
The latest response of Cambodia on the issue was a positive
development but some details still needed clarification, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot say a formal agreement has been reached until the
Cambodian parliament adopts legislation conforming to the
understandings reached between the United Nations and the Prime
Minister(Hun Sen)", the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"A formal agreement may be signed " after the Cambodian
parliament adopts legislation on the understandings reached
between the U.N. chief and the Cambodian Prime Minister, the
spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen sent a letter to U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan on May 19, supporting a compromise
formula based on the negotiations in April in Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
Annan agreed to wait until the Cambodian parliament adopts
legislation and offered to send Hans Corell back for further
discussions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
