<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets End Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 24 (Xinhua) - European stock markets ended mainly
lower Wednesday, with "new economy" shares extremely volatile.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index, lifted by a powerful surge of Britain'
s blue chip banking stocks, rose 0.52 percent, or 31.80 points, to
close the session at 6118.6.
</P>
<P>
Bank stocks came to the rescue in the market, bailing it out
from the volatility affecting the telecom, media and technology
sectors. Lloyds TSB rose more than 8 percent, and shares of
Barclays, Norwich Union and Bank of Scotland all gained about 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
The casualties in London came from the media and technology
sectors, with Colt Telecom some 9 percent lower and Cable &AMP;
Wireless down by 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The main victim in Frankfurt was steel maker ThyssenKrupp.
Investors punished the firm for failing to match expectations with
first-half earnings by hammering the shares nearly 14 percent
lower.
</P>
<P>
A 2 percent decline in Deutsche Telekom shares also hit the
market. The Xetra Dax slipped 1.34 percent, or 92.81 points, to
6834.88.
</P>
<P>
Chip maker STMicroelectronics led the way lower in Paris,
falling 7.3 percent to mirror the sharp slide in its Asian peers
overnight.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 index closed 1.98 percent lower at 6027.1,above its
session low of 6005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
