<HEADLINE> Colombian Attorney General Recommends to Suspend Neutral Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bernal warned that there is not a clear regulation on the norms
that must rule the demilitarized territory, to which peasants
living inside of it, who have not received clear information,
oppose blocking highways in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Negotiations with the communities are necessary," said the
Attorney General, who belongs to a civil mediation committee that
seeks to save a peace agenda agreed upon by the National
Liberation Army (ELN), the second most important guerrilla group
in the country, after the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (
FARC).
</P>
<P>
Bernal criticized the Government of President Andres Pastrana
for having agreed upon the creation of a buffer zone for the ELN
without consulting beforehand the residents of the region.
</P>
<P>
The Attorney General presented his advise when thousands of
peasants of north and northeast Colombia villages completed a two-
week period blocking the main highways communicating the interior
of the country with the Caribbean shores.
</P>
<P>
Residents of the zone protested for a recent decision of the
Government and the ELN to set up a "coexistence zone" in a little
less than 5,000 square kilometers within the municipalities of San
Pablo, Cantagallo and Yondo, the first two in the province of
Bolivar and the other in Antioquia.
</P>
<P>
According to leaders of the regions' communities, these are
afraid of the ELN causing the excessive behavior practiced by the
FARC in the southern zone of distention for the peace talks
between this guerrilla group and the Government.
</P>
<P>
The blocking of road traffic has caused severe losses to the
carriers and a lack in supply of agricultural products to the
markets in northern Colombia.
</P>
